INSERT INTO `posts` (`postId`, `postTitle`, `postText`, `postDate`, `subjectId`, `postTypId`, `fileId`, `adminId`, `statusId`, `imp`, `likeCount`) VALUES (1,'The House Call','<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>THE HOUSE CALL &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;-A story from Germany</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Characters</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Dr. Brawn &ndash;</strong> Famous German Surgeon</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Mrs. Brown &ndash;</strong> Wife of Dr.Braun</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Adelheide &ndash;</strong> Daughter of Elda&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Elda &ndash;</strong> Mother of adelheide</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Theme:</strong>&nbsp; Death can&rsquo;t put an end to Love&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The story is taken from Berlin City of Germany. The main characters are Dr. Emil Braun,&nbsp;Adelheide and a sick woman Elda.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">One day after Christmas of 1903, in the evening, Dr. Emil Brown of Germany was trying to make notes of the difficult surgical operation he did that day. He was trying to have dinner at the same time. But due to his tiredness he could not do either of them and soon dozed off.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Then a conversation about a house call between a small girl and his wife at his door woke him up. The child was saying that her mother was very ill and was dying soon. The doctor came to the door, talked to the girl. The girl of six or seven was thin and wearing cotton dress and shabby shoes. Dr. Emil became ready with his coat, hat and little black box despite his wife&rsquo;s disagreement.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">It was raining lightly. On the way the doctor tried to catch up the girl to ask some questions but the girl kept the distance between them and stopped for a short time only at the corners to make sure that the doctor was following.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The girl took him through the poorest part of Berlin, the section of the city around the hospital where he worked. Finally, the girl led him to an old house. They climbed the stairs through the dark hallway. The doctor tried to catch the girl on the stairs also but failed again. However, he felt energetic to climb up the stairs as if he was young. On the fifth floor the girl led the doctor to a room where woman was lying on a single bed. The girl thanked the doctor as he moved in and softly shut the door from outside. The elderly doctor easily recognized the woman. She worked as maintenance staff in the same hospital three years before. The doctor easily found out that the woman was suffering from pneumonia and gave her some medicine. He asked her if she had gone to live with her brother in country. The woman replied that she had gone but she had come back three months ago after her child&rsquo;s death. They talked about the woman&rsquo;s daughter confusingly. Then the woman showed her daughter&rsquo;s shawl and shoes to the doctor in the corner of the room. The doctor examined them carefully. The doctor touched them and felt that they were wet. He was astonished to this. Then the woman said that there might have been some confusion about the girl who called the doctor. The doctor agreed. The woman said that she had been thinking about him and he came which was strange. The woman slept with her half sentence and the doctor left the room.</p>','2014-05-28 01:54:23',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(2,'The Recurring Dream','<p><strong>THE RECURRING DREAM</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-A story from England<strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Characters</strong><br /><strong>Kimblerly Clark</strong> &ndash; Protagnasit (Main Character)<br /><strong>Janet Wilson</strong> &ndash; Roomate<br /><strong>Old man</strong></p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Theme</strong><br />-Outlet of suprresed Desire<br />-Link of dream and Reality</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>The story starts with a description of Kimberly Clark, the protagonist of the story, who is twenty five yeas old with all qualities of a normal young woman. She is pretty, she loves to dance, and she has many friends and a good position in the office of a large company. Despite these all, she has a problem. She has been troubled by a strange and mysterious dream that haunts her every night. <a name=\"more\"></a></p>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The strange dream always begins on a country road. Kim stands on this road and sees a lane with a white fence and a hedge on each side. At the end of the lane, on the top of a little hill, she sees a small white cottage with green shutters. Then she walks up the lane to the house, goes in and looks around. In one of the rooms, she finds a man asleep in bed. He is a little old man with white hair and a white heard. When she comes near his bed, the man wakes up. Then he sits up and looks at her. When she tries to speak to him, she wakes up. She is very surprised troubled by the dream because she has never known any little old man like that and neither the place.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">Kim&rsquo;s roommate knows everything. So, one day she proposes Kim to visit her (Janet&rsquo;s) parents&rsquo; farm house to feel peace in mind. As they pass through a country road, Kim sees the similar scene which she sees in her dream. They stop there. Janet does not want Kim to go and see the small cottage but Kim goes.</div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\">The house was exactly the same, except for a sign in front of the house which said &lsquo;FOR SALE&rsquo;. Unlike her dream, Kim goes to the door of the house and knocks and to her surprise the same old man answers the door who immediately closes the door. After Kim&rsquo;s request, he opens the door. Kim again asks why the house is for sale. The old man reveals that the house is haunted by a ghost. Kim tries hard to think to say something instead asks who the ghost is. The old man gets surprised and shocks her by replying that she herself is the ghost.</div>','2014-05-28 11:16:04',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(3,'The Recurring dream','<p><strong>Why do you think Kim has this dream?</strong><br />&ldquo;The Recurring Dream&rdquo; is the story from England.It is the story of Kim who has the same dream regularly. I think Kim has the same dream again and again because of her supressed desire and stressed mind.</p>\r\n<p>The father of psychoanalysis, Sigmund Frued said that &ldquo;Dreams are fulfilled of repressed desire.&rdquo; In the story , Kim has a normal ife, easy going.She lives and works in London,is pretty and young.But she has a mysterious dream time and again.She dream she is on a country road.She stands stands on this this road and sees a lanewith white fence and hedge on a both side.At the end of the lane is a white cottage with green shutters .She goes inside the house and finds a man with whitw beard and white hair.She comes near to the bed and tries to speak to the man but everytime when she tries to talk to the old man, she wakes up.I think she has this dream regularly because deep inside her she has a desire to leave the busy town and live in quiet peaceful environment.In the dream,there is an ld man.Also , no family of Kim are shown in the story.Kim want someone who can take care of her like her parents.The old man is like father figure to Kim. Also, due to the dream she is stressed and thinks about it way too much. Her work in company also adds the stress making her want peace and quiet environment.</p>\r\n<p>So, I think the main reason Kim has this dream is because of her supressed desire and stressful life.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>What do you think is the reason for the pepole having recuriing deams?</strong><br />Signund Fried, the father of psychoanlaysis said that, &rdquo;Dreams are disguised fulfilment of supressed desire&rdquo;.Dreams are the series of thought image sensations occuring in the mind during sleep. Dreams is common to all i.e. all people dream during their sleep. But some people dream the same thing frequently. I think some of the main cause for this recurring dream are supressed desire,stress,psycological problem and others.</p>\r\n<p><br />Mankind have a lot of desire.all of those desires are not possible to be fulfilled. But people have huge wishes to gett what the dream of. So, The dream shows our desire that are supressed deep inside of us and not fulfilled. Also ,when people stress about the same thing for a long period of time, the dream may occur frequently.Maybe pepople have some physical problem. Like seeing things really not present (hallucination) then they might also have a repeated series of the same dream. In such case Kim in the given story,it is showed that she have a busy life. Due to this busy scheudle she may not have been able to fullfil her desires.In this dream she always goes to the country side where there is a lane with white fence and hedge on both side and a cottage at the end of the lane.Since,she live in town, may be her desire are to have a peace, quite life.Also,there is an old man in her dream.This can also be taken as her lack of family affection and love.The old man shown in the story can be taken as a faher to Kim.Kim&rsquo;s life,though seem easy,was stressful enough due to this dream.She used to stress too much about the dream.It is said that she used to see it frequently at beginning.May be she stressed too much about it,which caused to occur on real basis.</p>\r\n<p><br /> In short,I think the reasons for reccuring dream are stress,supressed desire and psycological problems.</p>','2014-05-28 11:17:51',5,2,NULL,2,1,0,0),(4,'The House Call','<p><strong>If the doctor was too tired to eat or sleep, why was he not too tired to go to see the sick women?</strong><br />The doctor was too tired to eat or sleep but went to see the sick woman. This is because the doctor was a religious person and he believed he was to fulfill anything god will put in front of him.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Why do you think the little girl walked ahead of the doctor instead of walking with him?</strong><br />She was a Spirit who doesn&rsquo;t want to reveal her secret. So, In order to avoid the conversation with the doctor, she walked ahead.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Write a paragraph describing Dr. Braun?</strong><br />Dr. Braun full name is Emil Brown who is 67 years old. He is a very religious kind of a person who will do whatever god put in front of him. He was a famous a head Surgeon at the hospital. He put his duty in front of everything else.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Do you think it&rsquo;s a good idea to keep remainders of lost loved ones as Elda did?</strong><br />No. I think the best gift we can gave to our lost loved one is to forget them because our love one wouldn&rsquo;t want to see our suffering. In case, we keep some remainder of lost one, then we will always remember what we had and lost. It&rsquo;s just a waste of time. It won&rsquo;t give any benefit to the lost one or us. Life will be very hard remembering the happy days in sad times. So you should learn from your past. WE should rather believe in future.<br />Do you think Elda&rsquo;s Hoping and praying had anything to do with the doctor&rsquo;s coming to see her? Explain<br />Yes, BECAUSE the little girl who got the doctor must have heard her mother&rsquo;s prayer.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Write a paragraph explaining why do or don&rsquo;t believe that people stime appear after Death, like this in the story?</strong><br />Our body consisted of the physical body and soul. Once we die physical body dies but our soul, it moves from one place to another. If there is something the soul wants badly or something the soul left undone, the soul comes back. So, I believe that once a person dies, they appear after death.</p>','2014-05-28 11:30:20',5,2,NULL,2,1,0,0),(5,'The Lost Doll','<p><strong>The Lost Doll</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-A story from Colombia, South America</p>\r\n<p><strong>Characters:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Maria del Carmen: </strong>First Daughter</p>\r\n<p><strong>Rosa Soto: </strong>Mother of Maria del Carmen and Evangelina</p>\r\n<p><strong>Roberto Soto: </strong>Father of Maria del Carmen and Evangelina</p>\r\n<p><strong>Evangelina:</strong> Second Daughter</p>\r\n<p><strong>Theme- </strong>Recarnation, Rebith</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Maria Del Carmen is the only child of Roberto and Rosa Soto. She is beautiful, right, kind and loving child. However, she is sick from the day of her birth. As time passes, she becomes more and more weak and finally she dies when she turns four. Since everyone in the village loves the child, all of them attend her funeral. They bury the child in the cemetery outside the village. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;After some days, Rosa gives Carmen&rsquo;s clothes and playthings to the priest from another village. She gives them so that she will be able to forget Carmen easily. Moreover, the doctor says that she won&rsquo;t be able to give birth to another baby after Carmen. But Roberto doesn&rsquo;t become happy to hear this. He wants to save the things because he still hopes that Rosa will give birth to another child. He consoles her that because Rosa was busy in taking care of Carmen, god didn&rsquo;t send her another child. Roberto then remembers the doll with which Carmen often used to play and asks Rosa whether she has given that doll too. But Rosa says the doll was not with other things. They search for the doll everywhere but they can&rsquo;t find it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Rosa becomes pregnant and on the first anniversary of the death of Carmen she gives birth to another baby. It was good news for them so the priest also gives the name &lsquo;Evangelina&rsquo; to the child which means good news. As Evangelina grows up she looks more and more like Carmen. Her actions and characters are also similar to her sister. The only difference is that Evangelina is healthy. One day, when Evangelina turns four, she asks her mother whether she was sick for a long time back. But the mother says it was not she but her sister was sick. Evangelina insists that she remembers it very well and also asks her auntie about it. She also adds that she had a doll with blue eyes and red dress and she had put it under a big tree in the yard. She then takes them to that place and asks to dig there. When they dig the ground they find the doll there. Rosa can&rsquo;t believe her eyes and becomes speechless. But when Rosa&rsquo;s sister asks Evangelina to tell everything about what she remembers, she says that when she was sick the priest prayed with his hand on her head. Then she went to sleep. A real nice man woke her up and took her. But he didn&rsquo;t allow her to take the doll with her. So, she put the doll under the tree. Rosa becomes shocked when she hears the whole story. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; This is the story of reincarnation or rebirth in which Carmen is reborn as Evangelina. She is not only reborn but remembers everything that happened to her in her previous life.</p>','2014-05-28 11:41:03',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(6,'The Lost Doll','<p><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong><span style=\"border: 0px none; font-size: medium; font-style: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px none; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\"> How were Carmen and Evangelina alike and different? Or In what ways Mariya Del Carmen and Evangelina alike?&nbsp;</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">Evangelina was Rosa\'s second daughter and Carmen was the first one. Evangelina\'s actions and body structure were similar to her sister Carmen who had died after being sick. Evangelina looked as Carmen. The difference was that Carman was sick but Evangelina wasn\'t sick.&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong><span style=\"border: 0px none; font-size: medium; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px none; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">&nbsp;What evidences are there in the story to show that the Soto family was poor?&nbsp;</span></strong></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">&nbsp;Roberto and Rosa were both husband and wife. They had little daughter who died at the age of four. When Roberto doesn\'t find the doll of Carmen, he wants to save that doll for next child. This shows the poor condition of Soto family. They were living a simple and ordinary life.</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\">\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\"><strong><span style=\"border: 0px; font-size: medium; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; vertical-align: baseline;\">Other Important Questions<br /></span></strong></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">1. Rosa said to her husband. \"False hope is not good\". When does hope become false? How can we know when hope is false?</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">2. Why did Rosa said that there was no reason to save Carmen\'s things?</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">3. Write your opining about Carmen in brief.&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">4. What could be the reasons for attending Carmen\'s funeral by almost everyone?&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">5. Do you believe \"The Lost Doll\" is a story of reincarnation? How was it possible for Evangelina to lead her parents to the site where the lost doll was buried?&nbsp;</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">6.Why did Roberto want to save Carmen\'s things?</span></div>\r\n<div style=\"background-color: white; border: 0px; color: #333333; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px; margin: 0px; outline: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: justify; vertical-align: baseline;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;\">7. Why did they name the new baby Evangelina? </span><br /><br /></div>\r\n</div>','2014-05-28 11:43:19',5,2,NULL,2,1,0,0),(7,'Fear','<p><strong>FEAR&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-A story from Peubla, Mexico</p>\r\n<p><strong>Characters</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Armando &ndash; </strong>Protagonist(Main Character)</p>\r\n<p><strong>Eva &ndash;</strong> Wife of Armando</p>\r\n<p><strong>Heavy Man</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>3 Teenager</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>THEME:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Mind in its own place can make heaven of hell and hell of heaven. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Armando Gonzalez is the main character of this story. In&nbsp;this story, Armando enters a large bank in Mexico City and gives the cheque and the pass book to the bank teller. The teller asked so many questions to him and he counted the money with load voice but he realized himself that everyone was going to be know how much he actually had. He was so nervous while everybody was watching towards him. He put the money into his baggy pants and went out. He was watched by everyone because he was putting his hat on back ward. He saw one rather heavy man there who looked at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=8980101433934957741\" name=\"more\"></a>him. His whole body was shaking. He was sure that he was being followed and the heavy man was going to rob his money. He waited for a bus putting his hand into the pocket. When he got on the bus, he noticed the heavy man also got on. When other people got on the bus, they also seemed to be looking at him. He thought of the money collected after all his hard work. After thinking so much, he decided to get off the bus. But he noticed three teen boys also got off with him. Armando thought that three boys were helpers of heavy man. Armando was waiting for another bus but three boys were looking at him because he had still his hat on backwards. He was very frightened after that he thought if they were about to rob him. He ran saying \"Help me\". He ran across the road through the fence into an old junk yard. But the boys followed him. He slipped and the boys finnaly caught up with him and asked why he was runnig away. Armando, who was very frightened, begged&nbsp;the boys not to take his money. But the boys asked \"What money?\". Armando asked why they got off with him. They answered that they were students and they had gone there for football tournament. But they said that they got on the wrong bus and they were talking with a heavy man about bus. Finally, he knew all the reality and put his hat forward and walked together along the street.</p>','2014-05-29 12:52:43',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(8,'Fear','<ol>\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>Why did Armando have the idea that everyone in the bank was watching him? What is the truth?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Because he as nervous with the amount and was scared as everybody knew what he had in his pocket as this was his life time saving. The truth was he was wearing his hat Backwards.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>What are the things which made Armando think that someone was going to rob him?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Everyone was staring at him at the bank.</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;The heavy man he met inside the bank</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;After when he came out at the bus station the same guy was standing beside him. When he kept his hand on the pocket Armando referred it as a gun.&nbsp; And on the bus travel his sense was highly alerted when he saw 3 teenager boys talking with the heavy man who followed Armando to the station where the dropped to fake the Heavy man.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>Do you think we sometimes make things worse rather than better when we get nervous?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Yes. When we go nervous our mind gets blank. We will not be able to work on our senses, It seems as a worst nightmare coming true. Getting nervous is a weakness which is not good as it mostly bring Negative impact.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>What kind of person was Armando?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Armando was an honest hardworking cobbler. He had earned his every penny by hard work and honesty. His bad side is getting nervous quickly, He is a watchful person. He notices things soon. He is a non-violent and wise character who has no intension to hurt others or get hurt.</p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>5. &nbsp;<strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Why is Armando Afraid of the heavy man on the bus?</strong><br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Armando had put his hat on backwards. Everyone is the bank looked at him. A heavy man also looked at him twice. While waiting for the bus, the fat man was next to him. Armando trembled with fear and his heart was beating faster. He thought that the man was following him. When the fat man put his hand in his pocket Armando thought that he was looking for a pistol to rob him. On the bus three boys were talking to the fat man. Armando thought they were his helpers.&nbsp;<br /><strong><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </strong>6. &nbsp;<strong> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;What made Armando think that someone was going to rob him?</strong><br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;The main thing which made things worse was Armando&rsquo;s fear or nervousness. The cashier counted the money loudly. Many people in the bank looked at Armando as he had worn the hat on backward. The heavy man who looked at him twice in the bank followed him and got in the same bus. He put his hand in his pockets as if he were looking for pistol. Three boys who talked to the fat man got off with Armando and ran after him. All things made Armando thinks that he was being robbed.</p>','2014-05-29 12:58:01',5,2,NULL,2,1,0,0),(9,'The Loving Mother','<p><strong>The Loving Mother</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;-A story from Island of Hokkaido, Japan</p>\r\n<p><strong>CHARACTERS</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Shoji-</strong> Pharmacist</p>\r\n<p><strong>Young Women</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Mr.Sakotas&rsquo;s friend-</strong> A photographer</p>\r\n<p><strong>A child-</strong> 8 or 9 months</p>\r\n<p><strong>Setting :</strong> Pharmacy Winter Night 1964</p>\r\n<p><strong>Theme:</strong> Death can&rsquo;t prevent love.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Shoji Sakota was pharmacist in Japan who lived alone in the building where he had a drug store because his wife had died many years ago .As he lived in same building he sometimes worked in the drug store late at night .One particular stormy night while he was preparing annual business report, as it was the end of the year, he heard a knock on the door .He ignored it and worked continuously. He heard the knock again thought it was caused due to wind. When he heard the knock for the third time, that was louder than before, he thought it was emergency. He went to the door, lifted the shade and put on the outside who seemed very nervous. He thought it might be the trick of women to rob him, so he said the shop had been closed and said to come on next morning. When she requested him to give something for her baby and said that was dying, he opened the door.<br />The women took an ame on the stick. She seemed abnormally pale, had shoulder length hair and she was wearing simple kimono that seem it had been worn to bed. He gave her an ame and paying money for it, she went quickly. Sakota stops working and thought about the woman. He found the woman quite mysterious. Her eye shows that she was from another world. The same thing repeated for another two nights. He wanted to ask her why she had not come on the day time but forgot when she was there. One night he asked his friend to take the photo of the woman to look at her face clearly. When she came again his friend took a photograph hiding behind the door, to their surprise the woman was not seen though they had seen her through the lens of camera. They decided to follow her if she came again.<br />When she came again they followed after she went away from the store. She didn&rsquo;t mind them coming after her. Actually, she acted as if she wanted to be followed. After walking for some time she enters a building, goes up to the third floor and disappears. They saw an open door open and went inside. There in the room they saw a baby licking an ame. There was the person who was sleeping beside the baby. They were surprised to see the woman sleeping so fast. They thought she was pretending of sleeping. Sakota went closer to her and touched her body but she didn&rsquo;t move. She was cold and lifeless.&nbsp;The woman was dead. In fact, she had died many days ago....</p>\r\n<p><strong>Describing the Women</strong></p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Very thin</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Abnormally light skin</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Long, Black hair</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Worn out kimono</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eyes(looked like from another world)</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mysterious</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Float in the street, No legs</p>\r\n<p>The woman described in the story came only at night but never during daytime. She was very thin and had abnormally ligh skin. She had long, black hair and wears wron out kimona. Her eyes in particular frightened Mr. Sakota. They look to be from another world and lokked through you rather than look at you. She had very mysterious character adn when she walked away, she seem to float through the street rather than walk like a normal human.</p>','2014-05-29 13:28:40',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(10,'The Loving Mother','<ol>\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>What do you think Mr. Sakota meant when he said the woman&rsquo;s eyes looked like they belonged to someone from another world?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think Mr. Sakota meant to say that the women&rsquo;s eye weren&rsquo;t normal eyes when he said the women&rsquo;s eyes looked like they belong to someone from another world. Her eyes seemed to look through him, like the women knew everything about me, Sakota in just one look, just like reading his mind.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><strong>Write a paragraph about the woman?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I think the woman was a poor lady. She was very loving towards her child. She did not have any friends, though because she was all alone. She must be a spirit who has died due to poverty. She had nothing to give to her child. She was a traditional Japanese lady who was wearing the Cultural Outfit of japan. The torn out clothes represent her poverty. She always came to Mr. Sakota for an ame.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>3.<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Show the points of similarities and differences between the supernatural stories\" A House Call\" and \"The Loving Mother\"&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Both the stories `A House Call\' and `The Loving Mother\' are the supernatural stories. In the story `The House Call\' a small girl\'s spirit comes and visits doctor. Similarly in the story `The Loving Mother\' the spirit of death mother comes and visits the pharmacist. In both stories there is description of love and affection between the mother and the child. Both stories show that even after someone\'s death, their spirit visits their loving members of the family. The difference is that in the story of `The House Call\' small girl visit the doctor but in the second story the mother visits the pharmacist. In the first story, the little girl requests the doctor to get to her house but in the second story, the mother asks for ame.</div>','2014-05-29 13:33:43',5,2,NULL,2,1,0,0),(12,'My Heart Leaps When I Behold','<p><strong>MY HEART LEAPS WHERE I BEHOLD&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-William Wordswoth</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Poet Discription</strong></p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 19<sup>Th</sup> century poet</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nature loving poet</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; He worshipped nature through poem,</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Started trend of writing simple poem</p>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Calmness and serenity are the main ingredients of the poem</p>\r\n<p><strong>Poem Summary</strong></p>\r\n<p>The poem&nbsp;\"My Heart Leaps up When I Behold\"&nbsp;is composed by the famous English romantic poet William Wordsworth. In the poem, the poet describes the beauty of nature and shows his love and devotion towards nature. The poet recollects an experience of his childhood days and gives meaning to his emotions and feelings. Through his poem, the poet also shows the thread of human life i.e. progress or stages of our life.</p>\r\n<p>Wordsworth was a lover of nature. He worshiped the things of nature as god. He enjoyed the beauty of nature every time. In the poem, he says that when he sees the rainbow in the sky, he becomes very happy. Rainbow is the example of the beautiful creation of the nature. It looks really beautiful in the combination of seven colors. The poet further says that he used to happy when he saw the rainbow in the sky during his childhood days. The feeling of happiness for the rainbow is same in him as a young man at present. And he hopes to have the same types of feeling for the rainbow in future as well. He says that if he can\'t continue to have such feelings for nature in his future life, he feels it will be better for him to die.</p>\r\n<p>Finally, the poet expresses his wish for the future. He wishes to continue his love for the nature. In a sense, he wants to spend his future days worshiping the natural things. It is written in nine lies in which he has been able to show his love and devotion for nature and its beauty.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The paradox in \"The child is father of the man.\" &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In the poem, the poet says \'The child is father of the man.\' This proverb seems to be paradoxical as we consider the man to be father of man. But the poet wants to say that childhood is the base of every man\'s life because from childhood, manhood begins. Man enters the living world and starts to know life from his childhood. It determines the coming stages of our life. It is often said, morning shows the day, and in this context, it is obvious that the person shows same characters in his manhood which he gained or developed in childhood. In another words, the poet means to say that present is the outcome of the past so the future will be the outcome of the present. It indicates, the beginning of everything is very important. Here, the word father means the one from whom something begins. So it means, childhood is the foundation of manhood. A man goes towards his destiny which he determined himself in childhood. This indirectly points to the fact that man is himself controlled through his own childhood.&nbsp;Thus, childhood is the foundation of manhood and a child has roles as of father to play at present to mould himself in future as a man.</p>','2014-05-29 13:57:51',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(13,'My Heart Leaps When I Behold','<ol>\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong><strong>&nbsp;Write in one sentence what poem is about?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The poem is love and respect towards the nature towards the nature.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>Explain the paradox in &ldquo;The child is a father of man&rdquo;?</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Child is a father of the man. William Wordswroth quoted it in his poem; I think a child is a father of man because of his proximity to nature. A child is innocent and is close to nature. S/he plays in nature, spend times in nature and grow up in the nature. Due to this innocence they are superior to those men who don&rsquo;t have time for their own work and don&rsquo;t care about nature. Moreover a mad of today was a child of yesterday and a child of today will be a man tomorrow, AS morning shows the day, Childhood determines the manhood of a man, those who had good learning in childhood turns to be a good person and likewise. Their learning in childhood is what makes them closer to nature and father of man.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n<li><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>Summaries the poem in a paragraph.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;MY heart leaps when I behold is a poem written by William Wordsworth. He shows his love to nature through his poem. He said he becomes happy when he sees the rainbow, in the nature. His life begins then in nature. He feels joyful when he sees the colorful rainbow, the rainbow stays the same when he turned into a man and grew old. If the nature didn&rsquo;t exist or died as we grow up, then the poet says, he doesn&rsquo;t want to live. A life without nature is meaningless. Even nature makes a child father of man. The closeness of child to nature and his ability to understand nature is vast. The poet wishes he could spend his life with nature and be united to the nature.</p>','2014-05-29 13:59:57',5,2,NULL,2,1,0,0),(14,'Looking at The Tea Cup','<p>1.&nbsp;<strong>Expalin &ldquo;The cup is a detail, a small unchatted finger from mid-cenyury bonfire.&rdquo;</strong></p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The cup is a detail, a small unchatted finger from mid-cenyury bonfire&rdquo;. The cup in the sentence refers to the cup bought by thr writer&rsquo;s mother in 1939 which was a souviner handed to her, The Tea cup was thin, palest water green imaginable. Sometimes, in certain lights it is so pale, it doesn&rsquo;t seem green at all.It is shiny, and there are thin bands of gold cup and again midway down th bowl of the cup and it&rsquo;s base, which is subtly formed into a semi-pedestal. There is also a band of gold on the inner circle of the saucer,but it has been worn away after so many years of use. Inside the cup there are flowers, as if some one has scattered a bouquet and it had tumbled into seperate blossoms, falling in a full circke around the inside.Some had already fallen wheras some were still falling.No flowers in the cup were simillar.<br /> <br />The cup was one part of the history not beacuse it was too old but it had lived through the destruction cauesd by Second Wolrd war. Many and many things fell that yeat but the cup was still safe. In other way, the cup was safe because someone had looked after it. Here,the easiest wants to imply that the second world war could also had been avoided had they taken good steps. Bodies fell in Europe but the tea cup had no scratch on it. The second world war was the most devasting war of man kind, Many inncocent, were killed and Billions of worth Property were destroyed.And even in Barcelona, almost for the 1st time in history a woman carrying a bunch of Forsythia wrapped in waxed paper ran for cover,hidding from air.The newborns died without seeing what world had to offerm Many women wrere widowed and many childern were Orpahned. Humanity had also Died along with the war. So, this war brought down everything along with it.</p>\r\n<p>In short, the lines wants to say how we could have protected ourself or avoided the second world war by only taking good care of our own nation.</p>\r\n<p>2. <strong>What do you mean by&rdquo; Many things fell that year&rdquo;?</strong><br />&ldquo;Many things fell that year&rdquo;. This line is reffereing to the year 1939, begginning of the seound world war. In 1939,everything fell. The flowers in the tea cup fell, This symbolically represent Bombs falling from the year adn some already landed taking thousands and thousand sof inncoents lives. Just like the flowers in tea cup, the bombs were landing, Many dead bodies have fallen that year.</p>\r\n<p>When there is a war,development also stops.once development stops, a country falls.In1939,the country fell,thery wew never upgraded again.Just like Czekoslovakia, the cup made were sold but the skill had alreaday fell.Our own human civilization which taught us our lessons and kindness fell. For the first time bodies of bride paired with other bodies fell on bed. Our Tradition and culture lesson fell.They proved to be wrong.All dreams and hopes one had for fututre fell due to the war only because one had to serve the country.Many women were widowed and many men were killed.This decreased the faith in marriage and finally faith in marriage fell. War had made men cruel and didnt care about anyone else . So, the greatest of all humanity fell that year.</p>\r\n<p>So, everything fell that year starting from falling of flowers to humanity.</p>\r\n<p>3.<strong> How does Hampel see herself and her mother connected by the tea cup?</strong><br />\"Look at the tea cup\" is a essay that is completly depended upon the tea cup.Here the tea cup is the medium for all questioned asked in the essay.The tea cup was brought by Hampel mother in 1939.She preserved it and handed it to her daughter.</p>\r\n<p><br />The essay talks about the realtionships of mother and daughter.In this essay the mother is a silent kind of women. Whereas her daughter is a talkative one.The daughter wants to know many things about the past.But her mother sayd that there was no significant in her life.But the daughter didnt agree.Beacuse she had survived the war. At that time even europe started to eat itself raw.The daughter however thought her life was very significant due to it. The mother passed down the teacup as a soviner. This is where all the questions start to rise.The daughter looks at the cup and all the questions abut her mother past stars to come out.This cup has helped her to understand the life of her mother life better than ever before. She understood the life of women in 1939 because of her mother. The mother doesnt talk about her life.This shows the way a women wants to keep all her pain to herself.</p>\r\n<p>In short, the tea cup is where all the sumberged figure starts coming out and all the past connected to her mother comes out.</p>','2014-05-29 14:03:20',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(48,'Cytology,Cell and Cell totipotency','<h4>Cell biology</h4>\r\n<p>It is the branch of science which we study about structure and function of cell.</p>\r\n<h4>Cytology</h4>\r\n<p>It is the branch of biology in which we study about the structure, components, function and cell division.</p>\r\n<h4>Cell</h4>\r\n<p>The term cell was derived from the Latin word &lsquo;Cella&rsquo; which refers to the empty compartments or cell. It can be defined as the basic structural and functional unit of life because it gives shape of body of different living organisms Except WBC &amp; amoeba. It also carries out all the biological process. All the living organisms are made up of cell.</p>\r\n<h4>History of Cell</h4>\r\n<p>After the invention of microscope the cell was discovered by physicist Robert hook in 1665. During his period he took a slice of a cork and observed under the microscope, he found that there are number of empty compartments like honey comb. He named each Compartment as a cell. The he took again a Slice of living parts as roots, stem, leaf etc. and observed under the microscope. In this case Number of chambers was observed but each chambered compartment contains something inside it, such chambers are named as cell.</p>\r\n<h4>&nbsp;The cell Theory</h4>\r\n<p>Cell theory was first coined by the Scheleiden and Schwann in 1839. According to the Scheleiden all the plant bodies are made up of cells and similarly According to the Schwann all the animal bodies are made up of cell. Now the combined Views of both scientists Forms a theory called Cell Theory.This theory states that</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All the living bodies are made up of cells.</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This cells are derived from the Pre-existing cells</p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All the living bodies have basically similar properties, compounds &amp;activities.</p>\r\n<p>4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All the functions carried out by the living organisms are activities and interaction of cell components.</p>\r\n<p>5)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Growth and development takes place in unicellular organisms by cellular growth. But in case of multi cellular organisms it takes place by cell division.</p>\r\n<h4>&nbsp;Drawbacks Of cell theory</h4>\r\n<p>The theory can&rsquo;t be applied in all cases. There are some weak points which cannot be explained by this theory. They are:-</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bacteria and cyanobacteria don&rsquo;t contain complete nucleus. It only has got a naked bundle of chromosome. Such nucleus is called indefinite, incipient or Nucoid.</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In virus, there is no cellular organization. It has only DNA or RNA &amp; protein</p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In some primitive algae and fungi protoplasm is not spates &amp; multinucleated. Such type of body is called Coenocyte body.</p>\r\n<p>4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There are many nonliving things which are found inside the cell but the cell theory can&rsquo;t explain non-living things.</p>\r\n<h4>Cellular totipotency</h4>\r\n<p>All the vegetative cells of the plant body have got the potentiality to form the entire plant; such capacity of the plant is called cellular totipotency. It was first coined by Hoertland in 1902 &amp; experimentally proved by the F.C steward in 1957.</p>\r\n<h4>Steward Experiment</h4>\r\n<p>The experiment was performed in the carrot root. He took a few phloem cells from the carrot root and kept in the culture tube containing artificially prepared medium and coconut milk. Then grow under the controlled environment. After few days the phloem cells divide repeatedly divides and produce young embryo. Now the embryo is then transferred into next culture tube containing same nutrition. Then it further develops and then produces young plantlet and it is transferred in a pot and grew up in the open environment. Each plantlet develops into the entire plant. In this way, steward proved that entire plant is produced from the phloem cells. Such capacity of cell is called cellular-totipotency.</p>\r\n<h4>Types of living Body</h4>\r\n<p>According to number of cells there are two types of living organisms. They are:-</p>\r\n<h3>Unicellular organism</h3>\r\n<p>If the living body is made up of single cell and those living organisms are called unicellular organisms. It has simple structure and carries all the biological process E.g. amoeba, paramecium</p>\r\n<h4>Multicellular organism</h4>\r\n<p>If the living body is made up of more than one cell then it is call multicellular organism. The structure of multicellular living organism is more complex with increasing the number of cells. In case of multicellular, zygote divide many times to form mass of cells among them grouping and division of labor take place. Each group of cell is called tissue. And the numbers of systems produce life in this way cell, tissue organ, systems are interrelated to each other.</p>\r\n<h4>Flow of energy through cell</h4>\r\n<p>In the living beings to carry out the function, cell needs the constant supply of energy. In this living world earth, Sun is the major source of energy. The sunlight is captured by the chloroplast by the green cell. And then prepare the food with the help of photosynthesis process. Then some of the food is transferred to the animals or non-green plants in the form of grains, root, fruits etc.</p>\r\n<p>In the green cell, the foods produced by the photosynthesis are transferred to the mitochondria and then the food get oxidized and turned to the energy. Some of the energy is transferred to the cell to carry out the system activities. And the remaining amount of the energy is stored in the form of ATP. In the absence of food in the cell, mitochondrion releases the energy to run the system in the cell. So-called the power house of the cell.</p>\r\n<p>Similarly in the Non-green plants or animals; the food provided by the green cell is transferred to the mitochondria. And the oxidation of food takes place. And some amount of energy is used by the cell to run the system but the remaining amount of energy is stored in mitochondria in the form of energy. And whenever the crisis of energy takes place it release he energy so called the power house of cell.</p>','2014-06-03 21:56:43',3,1,NULL,4,1,0,0),(47,'Keeping Things Whole','<p><strong>Keeping Things Whole</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-Mark Strand</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Theme</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Human quest of finding wholeness</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Mark&nbsp;<span id=\"s90au10i_6\" class=\"s90au10i\">Strand</span>&nbsp;in his poem&nbsp;&ldquo;Keeping things Whole&rdquo;&nbsp;expresses that&nbsp;<span id=\"s90au10i_3\" class=\"s90au10i\">human beings</span>&nbsp;always disturb the nature whereas nature always makes a balance to keep itself intact. The poet appeals for wholeness of nature against its usual fragmentation while performing daily activities in our life.<br /><br />The poet says that while in the field, he considers himself as absence of the field; this is because the field is missing where he is&nbsp;<span id=\"s90au10i_8\" class=\"s90au10i\">standing</span>. Wherever he is in the field, he displaces and occupies the part of the field that is missing (not visible). According to the poet, he divides the&nbsp;<span id=\"s90au10i_5\" class=\"s90au10i\">air</span>&nbsp;when he walks. In other words, he disturbs the nature.&nbsp;</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">When he moves forward, the air comes from different directions to cover up the vacant space. In order to fulfill the desire, human beings always&nbsp;<span id=\"s90au10i_7\" class=\"s90au10i\">damage</span>&nbsp;and disturb the nature. However, the nature always makes a&nbsp;<span id=\"s90au10i_4\" class=\"s90au10i\">balance</span>&nbsp;by repairing itself. The poet tells us that while performing various activities in life, we should be very careful and should not disturb the nature rather we should support the wholeness of it. The poet says that people may have different reasons of moving, but the poet keeps moving to enable the nature to repair it by itself as he wants to keep the nature whole.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Meaning</strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">The poet is reflecting on his existence. He is apart from the day to day living shared by others. His presence is non existent as he believes he is what is missing in a field, while walking he is ghost-like displacing the air but then he is replaced by air. Again he is what is missing. He is aware his presence is disruptive so he keeps moving to keep his impact on any one place to a minimum. By doing this he is keeping things whole rather than fractured by his presence as where ever he is he is missing from the life of the scene and he would therefore be disturbing to those around him.&nbsp;<br />Here is a man who has not self actualised and has no positive thoughts concerning his being.&nbsp;<br />The poem is disturbing and sad in its sense of the loneliness of not belonging.</p>','2014-06-03 13:04:37',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(17,'The poplar Field','<p><strong>The Poplar Field</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-William Cowper</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Poet Discription</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">- Born&nbsp;Nov. 26, 1731</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-An English poet and&nbsp;hymnodist</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Changed the direction of 18th century nature poetry&nbsp;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Poem Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>William Cowper gave up his public career for a life of retirement in rural area and exclusively, devoted his later life in writing poetry. His love towards nature in rural life is also visible in the poem &ldquo;The Poplar Field&rdquo;, which is remarkable for his celebration for the rural and nostalgic tone.</p>\r\n<p>The poem is a result of the poet&rsquo;s second visit to the same landscape, which he had visited 12 years ago. It was the bank of river Ouse, which was filled with tall poplar trees. It provided shade to the poet. There used to blow cool breeze and the melodious song of black birds which had entertained the poet. But now the trees are cut and are fallen on the ground. It cannot provide shade to anyone nor there is cool breeze blowing. The black birds have flown away in search of new shelter and therefore, the poet cannot listen to their sweet songs anymore. By looking this degraded situation of the same landscape, the poet becomes very sad.</p>\r\n<p>The poet thinks that limited years of his life are passing away very quickly. Very soon he will be dead and buried in a grave. But he regrets that he will not be able to see such poplar trees on the bank of the river Ouse again in his life. He not only regrets for himself but the pathetic one of nature also draws his attention towards the &ldquo;Perishing Pleasure&rdquo; of human. Life is very short and one must try to fill with joy and pleasure. But their bad luck is their joy and pleasure last for shorter time and for this they themselves are responsible.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:10:26',5,1,NULL,5,1,0,0),(18,'The Poplar Field','<p><strong>Consider This Poem as a defense of nature Conservation.</strong><br />&ldquo;The poplar field&rdquo; by W.Cowper is created out of pain through the nature. This poem shows the change in nature before and now, the nature is shown by the poplar forest which represents all the nature and natural resources. The poplar field used to be dense, large and beautiful. But, now the poplars have felled. We have to bid farewell to the shade. The trees are now laid as lowly as the grasses. The tree that once used to give shade has been turned to the seat. The blackbirds are no longer there and along with them they have taken their sweet songs and melody. This have all been caused by we human, we are all destructing the nature without a care for tomorrow. We destroy our environment not knowing for tomorrow. The good nature and environment are a sight to look at. When our happiness is short and these are the things that make us happy then why do we destroy the things that make us happy? Why do we kill our own happiness?<br />So, The poet have told us to save our own happiness by saving the nature.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:11:15',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(19,'The Nightmare Life without Fuel','<p><br /><strong>The Nightmare life Without Fuel</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">- Isaac Asimov&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Theme:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Traumatic, frightening, terrifying, terrible, dreadful, horrendous, nightmarish life about Fuel Crisis</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<div>&ldquo;The Nightmare Life Without Fuel&rdquo; is an essay which depicts the life of this world in coming future when the fuel resources will have reduced from their source. The main thrust of this essay is: what is going to happen if we do not conserve the world&rsquo;s natural resources. Asimov focuses on a specific problem that will arise by the lack of fuels. This whole world is run by different resources such as petrol, diesel, water, wood, etc. We cannot imagine this world without the use of fuel. In comparison to the past days, we are now facing the problem of scarcity of fuel resources. Earlier these resources were found in large quantity and life style was easier.<a href=\"http://www.blogger.com/blogger.g?blogID=8980101433934957741\" name=\"more\"></a></div>\r\n<div>As the fuel resources were abundantly found, every sector was found running successfully and easily. Factories, industries, transportation, great organizations, etc. were in proper condition. People didn&rsquo;t have problem of scarcity of fuel resources. But slowly and gradually population growth increased and brought bad consequences. Agricultural lands were occupied by huge buildings and industries. Also, the number of vehicles also increased. Due to the maximum use of the resources, human life has been in discomfort. Human beings feel that their lives are really unsecured. They always have fear that they will lose work and food. They think that they are themselves responsible for causing scarcity of resources. As they are less conscious of their future, they suffer because of the destruction of the resources. Most of them claim that they will have new resources invented. Of course, new resources such as nuclear energy and solar power have been discovered but they are very dangerous and also expensive in use. People know that their pleasures are in danger and also their future is dark. Coming generations will suffer more than us.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Asimov focuses on the decreasing resources of fuel in the world. The life will be full of struggle without fuel resources. This world will slowly go dark, as less lighting bulbs will be there in the streets. Electrical appliances will be used less as there will also be scarcity of electricity. Even luxurious provisions and equipments will be impossible. More time will be taken to do simple work also as there won&rsquo;t be any vehicle running in the streets. There will be difficulty in transportation and accumulation of required foodstuffs. Due to the shortage of food, people will die due to starvation and malnutrition. Due to lack of proper balanced diet, there will be problem in human brains. Child death rate will increase, as children will be deprived of proper nutritious and body building food. Specially, simple towns, suburbs will be affected much. These areas depend upon transportation for all kinds of things. They will be in danger of extinction. Every human activity will be minimized due to less light, heat, and less comfort. Security forces will also be affected badly. Without the use of weapons, military forces will be purposeless. Their work will end because they can&rsquo;t work without fuel. They use scientific weapons, which are operated with fuel and are very expensive. Only the technically strong countries will be able to exercise their military power if fuel is saved in time. Factory workers will be jobless as industries and factories will be closed. So, it will be very difficult for them to provide basic needs to their family also.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Only small benefits will be there due to lack of fuel. The environment will be fresh, cool and pure. Crime rates will decrease. People will understand the importance of nature and will go attached with it. People will be cooperative, as all of them will be facing same problem. They will keep themselves warm using sweaters and other thick clothes only.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The writer tries to warn us from the devastating situation of this world in the coming future. If we are not serious at present only, we have to suffer a lot in the future. We must understand the importance of the nature and try to conserve it. The world is depending upon the trade and because of trade the environment is being neglected. People are living in the cities and the environment of the cities is polluted. Major population of world should be engaged to plant the trees to make a better world in future. We cannot use the solar easily and even if we use, it cannot naturally help us. But if we preserve the jungle, our environment and energy will be improved.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Synopsis of the Essay</strong></div>\r\n<div>The present essay written by the Russian writer Isaac Asimov basically concerns about the fuel shortage in the present world. He has given us the instances from America about how the fuel shortage directly or indirectly relates to human life and its adverse impacts. The writer kindly advises us to preserve the existing natural resources that give us the enormous fuel to sustain life. The essay &ldquo;The Nightmare Life Without Fuel,&rdquo; originally published in the Time Magazine in 1977, portrays America in the late 1990s, where the existing fuel resources have reduced this developed and rich nation to miserable condition of dark and dirty replica of the pre-industrial 1800s. America is just a small example to show how dwindling fuel resources have been reducing. The central essence of this essay is considerable that the worst condition may coome if we do not preserve the natural resources of the world.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The writer describes the terrific situation in the urban areas of America where people are wandering here and there for the fuel and energy. People gather in the subways where the bus is already left and bicycles are splashed on the muddy water, which indicates difficulties in life due to shortage of fuel. Coal is difficult to get by digging and nuclear fusion is very risky and then the solar batteries are very costly. The stuff of the decaying city should be the mineral mines to use again.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>There are several adverse impacts on human life due to fuel shortage; but the writer says that this kind of shortage would be beneficial to some extent. Automobiles are vanished and become the metal resources; likewise the ration system also will decrease. According to the writer, there are reports from the newspapers in 1997 that the environment becomes cleaner, crime rates are reduced and the policemen are returned to their beats. The streets are deserted and the legs of the people become superior in the street. People do not consume the expensive electricity; they are deprived of modern facilities. For them open air is the air condition and homemade sweaters are popular indoor wear.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The people in the city feel comfort rather than the people in suburbs. Energy crisis is the vital problem for the city dwellers. The nation should find the alternative source of energy to soothe the growing population. The condition outside USA and Europe is even worse and the people do not have sufficient food stuff to eat; only about one in five has enough food to eat. Rest of people would die of starvation. But the writer states that starvation reduces the world&rsquo;s population and more than two billion people suffer from brain damage due to less nutritious food. The fuel resources are limited, so it has the great impact on human life. The energy crisis is continued and as a result, the world&rsquo;s countries would not afford their cost, keep their soldiers for the long time and unable to feed their people properly. Because of fuel shortage, the electricity is not possible, the people will deprive of watching TV, movie and reading books and they will ultimately return to the age of 1800. Then the existing fossil fuel (natural fuel produced by decomposition of organic) will work out.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The agricultural system will also be destroyed, the new technologies will be halted due to fuel crisis and farmer cannot produce enough crops to sustain people&rsquo;s life. As a result more people will die of starvation. The situation will be havoc, to cope with such situation, we had to take step to improve the situation 50 years ago, and then it would have been quite better to cope with fuel crisis.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>It is indeed a serious issue to preserve the dwindling natural resources and if we do not think positively, it will devastate our society, and nation which are completely depended on fuel. The general people on the outskirt of the city (suburbs) will die untimely because of fuel shortage. The condition of poor nation will be perilous and the women and children&rsquo;s mortality rate will increase and those who remain alive also suffer from bad health. But in the case of rich nation, it won&rsquo;t be serious problem, they can afford their necessities and there will be the wider distinction between poor and rich people.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Finally the writer recommends us the possible solution of the current fuel crisis in the world. He strongly suggests preserving the natural resources though it is very late. The remaining natural resources will also make us relieve if we seriously ponder about it and do something for the sake of natural resources to tackle the fuel crisis.</div>\r\n<div>According to the essay fuel crisis will have following advantages and disadvantage:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>It has the following&nbsp;<strong>advantages</strong>:<br /><ol>\r\n<li>There will no smoke from vehicles and industries so the air will be pollution free.</li>\r\n<li>Less people will suffer from cough and cold because of pollution free air.</li>\r\n<li>Crime rate will fall down because of mutual protection in crowd.</li>\r\n<li>Due to lack of other entertainment facilities, people will start utilizing natural source of entertainment.</li>\r\n<li>People will learn to live natural life without facilities such as central heating, shower bath with hot water etc.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\nThe following will be the&nbsp;<strong>disadvantages of fuel crisis</strong>:<br /><ol>\r\n<li>People will be deprived from facilities which will make their life complicated.</li>\r\n<li>People will have to walk and carry goods by themselves.</li>\r\n<li>People living in suburbs will face acute problem bringing and storing food.</li>\r\n<li>High percentage of people will have health problems, even sustain brain damage</li>\r\n<li>Entertainment and printing materials will be curtailed depriving people from getting even information and news.</li>\r\n<li>There will be high death rate of infants as their mothers will go dry.</li>\r\n</ol></div>','2014-05-29 14:13:01',5,1,NULL,5,1,0,0),(20,'The NightMare life without Fuel','<p><strong>1. According to the author, what will be the advantage of the fuel crisis?</strong><br />Ans: To begin with it should be very clear that there&rsquo;s no advantage at all of fuel crisis. Still, however, the writer has mentioned some advantages of it. But, they are mentioned ironically.<br /> The first advantage of fuel crisis is that the air will be cleaner and there will be no air pollution. People will have fewer colds. People will walk freely in the streets and there will be no danger of accidents. The parks will be full. On the top of everything, people will communicate with each other freely and more frequently. There will be fewer crimes and the policemen will be back to their beats.<br /> On the other hand, there will be peace in the world. Only the United States and the Soviet Union will have some aero planes, ships and tankers. Even these countries will not be able to use such things. People will use things like sweaters, blankets and they will have fresh air in summer. People will complete their daily activities by the evening and will go to beds early at nights.<br /> There are many disadvantages of fuel crisis. All the scientific progress will come to a stop. The factories will be closed and there will be full unemployment. At the same time, there will be a total lack of different products in the market.<br /> Due to the lack of transportation, people of one end of the world will die out of hunger whereas there will be food supply in the other part of the world. Similarly, medicines also cannot be sent from one part of the world to another. In those countries where there will be lack of food, thousands of people will suffer from malnutrition and brain damage. All the activities will come to an end. Machines will be replaced by physical labour of human muscles and animals. In short, all the scientific progress will stop and human civilization will go back to the time before the industrial revolution or Stone Age.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>2. In Asimov&rsquo;s essay, what is happening in the rest of the world as America struggles without&nbsp;fuel?</strong><br />Ans: The writer shows a very dismal picture of the rest of the world as America struggles without fuel. People will be starving in many parts of the world. Perhaps, not more than one in five will have enough to eat. There will be a high rate of infant mortality. Due to the lack of food, there will be many cases of permanent brain damage by under nutrition. So much so, many such people will have to be killed out of mercy.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3. What does the author mean when he says, &ldquo;the suburbs were born with the auto, lived&nbsp;with the auto, and are dying with the auto.&rdquo;</strong> <br />Ans:&nbsp;Suburbs are the areas just outside the large cities. With rapid industrialization and development, the cities became crowded. Therefore people started living little away from the cities enjoying equal opportunities as cities. Because of easy availability of automobiles (vehicles), the suburbs were come into existence. People living in the suburbs are fully dependent on the cities for educational, medical facilities, for their employment and for their daily provisions. Due to easy vehicular movement, they are living happily availing facilities like cities. Now with the fuel crisis, there to and from movements to the city and vice-versa are restricted because of non availability of vehicles. The restriction deprives them from enjoying the facilities which they have been enjoying up to now. Therefore, the people living in suburbs are now facing extreme difficulties in their life as they are now dying with auto.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>4. What kinds of serious problems could a fuel shortage cause?</strong><br />Ans: i) No normal life &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;ii) No food <br /> iii) No transportation <br />iv) No industries <br />v) No production <br />vi) No employment&nbsp;<br /><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">vii) No civilization <br />viii) Malnutrition<br /> ix) Brain damage<br /></span><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">x) No Medicines </span><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\"><br />xi) Difficult to&nbsp;sustain our life&nbsp;</span></p>','2014-05-29 14:13:50',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(46,'A worn Path','<p><strong>A worn Path</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-Eudora Welty</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Characters</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Phoneix Jackson - Protagonist</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Grandson</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">White man</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Topics Discussed&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Racism</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Love</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Poverty</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Literacy</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary</strong></p>\r\n<div>&lsquo;A&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_4\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">Worn Path</span>&rsquo; is a story about an&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_3\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">old black</span>&nbsp;woman named Phoenix, who is courageous and endangers her life to get the medicine for her grandson, who is suffering from extreme throat pain. Literally speaking, the story is the story of journey of old woman who walks towards the city on the cold winter day. She is taking a long trip to the city to visit the hospital and bring some medicine for her grandson. This is not the first time she is going to the city. She goes there frequently for the&nbsp;medicine. She loves her grandson so much that she faces many trouble and obstacle on the long trip.</div>\r\n<div>This story is the live description of the journey of the old Negro woman. The writer presents live description of the real character so that the events of that story seem convincing. Phoenix comes up against several troubles between the valley and wagon track. She has to walk across thorny bushes and deep woods. She has to cross a river and even climb a steep hill. Her dress is caught and scratched by thorns. But, she frees herself with hard struggle. She has to creep and crawl under the barbed wire. She is even disturbed by the scarecrow, which she thinks to be a ghost. Later, she falls into a ditch when she tries to protect from the black dog. In spite of all these difficulties, she is successful to reach her destination.</div>\r\n<div>It is quite strange to the reader that she keeps talking to herself because she is alone on the way. Also, she is very old and talking alone has because her habit. By talking to herself, she tries to forget hardships and troubles that come on her way. Monologues add a lot to the total portrait of her habits, nature and attitude. Through the monologue we can read her mind. From her monologue she seems weak, kind-hearted and loving woman. She is the woman who is afraid of even small things. But, she finds way to remove her obstacles. She is uneducated and knows very little about the outside world. She has&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_2\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">lots of love</span>&nbsp;for her grandson but despite of her weakness she is determined woman who frees all the challenges of the life. Her monologues add a lot to the total portrait of her.</div>\r\n<div>Phoenix can be compared to the bird Phoenix in Egyptian mythology, which burns itself, changes into ashes and again recreates&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_7\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">new life</span>. In every obstacle, Phoenix seems to be losing hope such as burning of Phoenix bird into ashes. Later, when she gets victory over the obstacles, she seems to be regaining her hope such as recreation of life of Phoenix from ashes.</div>\r\n<div>She is a very poor woman. When she sees the nickel dropped from a white man, she thinks she can do something with&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_8\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">that money</span>. Her poverty drives her to pick up that nickel. She does this theft jus for good reason. She wants to&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_5\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">buy paper</span>&nbsp;windmill for her grandson as a surprise gift on the occasion of Christmas Day.</div>\r\n<div>At last, she is able to get success in her aim. In spite of her old age, she proves herself to be a courageous and determined woman. Being simple and uneducated lady also, she overpowers all the obstacles on her way due to her deep love for her grandson.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Trails she passed through in sequence</strong></div>\r\n<div>Age- Hills - Her dress get caught in the thorny bush- log - barbed wire fence - passing through the corn field- scary crow - black dog - memory loss</div>','2014-06-03 12:54:17',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(22,'Unchopping a Tree','<p><strong>Unchopping a Tree</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">W.S. Merwin</p>\r\n<p><strong>Theme:</strong>&nbsp;If we cannot unchop the tree then it&rsquo;s better not to chop the tree.</p>\r\n<p><br />In the essay &ldquo;Unchopping a Tree&rdquo;, the writer presents impossible example to convey deep meaning. Joining the chopped parts of trees refers to the new plantation of more trees in the open fields, which are full of stumps. Every part of trees refers to the every parts of the nature whether they are small or big. Each and every parts of nature is important. As we are also the creation of the nature, it is our duty to maintain the balance in the nature. We don&rsquo;t have rights to destroy the nature. Actually we are not destroying the nature but we are destroying ourselves. Our lives totally depend upon the nature. Through the writer&rsquo;s appeal to join the parts of the chopped trees, he wants to remind human beings about their important works to be done to conserve the greenery of the nature.</p>\r\n<p>Unchopping a tree is impossible. It is only a kind of feeling but certainly it has meaning. The writer emphasizes on the preservation of the nature. The nature should be preserved and those persons who cur the trees must plant some more in replacement. When they save and plant the trees, it is unchopping a tree. The writer warns that it is easy to destroy but very hard to create. He further says that life of a tree and human life are the same so they should be preserved with equal emphasis. Not only the trees we should save but also should protect the habitats of some animals who live in trees.</p>\r\n<p>The writer tries to persuade us how to work hard to bring the chopped tree into the original situation, which is not really possible. When a tree is felled down, there is no way to bring it into its original condition. But its place can be replaced with more trees, which we plant. Trees are also the important parts of the ecosystem as other living creatures. We should think of conservation of such trees instead of deforestation for the protection of the ecosystem.</p>','2014-05-29 14:17:35',5,1,NULL,5,1,0,0),(23,'The Three Day Blow','<p><br /><strong>The Three Day Blow</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-Ernest Hemingway&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Characters</strong><br /><strong>Nick &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Protagonist (Main Character)<br /><strong>Bill &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Nick&rsquo;s Friend<br /><strong>Marjorie &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Nick&rsquo;s Girlfriend</p>\r\n<p><strong>Settings</strong><br />Stormy weather autumn(fall)<br />Bill&rsquo;s House<br />Psychological Plot</p>\r\n<p><strong>Themes</strong><br />Love<br />Friendship<br />Relationships<br />Drinking</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>Summary</strong></p>\r\n<p>The story only has two major characters, Nick and Bill (Marge, Nick&rsquo;s father, and Bill&rsquo;s father are mentioned but do not make an appearance), and the entire story takes place either inside or outside of Bill&rsquo;s father&rsquo;s cottage.</p>\r\n<p>The story begins with Nick walking around the orchard near the cabin. He picks up a Wagner apple and puts it in his pocket. Nick climbs the stairs to the cottage and Bill meets him at the door, telling Nick that Bill&rsquo;s father is out in the woods with his gun. Bill and Nick stand together, looking out across the fields. They discuss the wind for the first time, with Bill saying &ldquo;It will blow like that for three days.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>After they go inside the cottage, they decide to drink. Initially, they drink a bottle of Bill&rsquo;s father&rsquo;s already opened whiskey, mixing it with water. Later on, they do the same with a bottle of scotch. Bill has Nick take off his shoes and dry them by the fire. The two begin to discuss a variety of topics while drinking, such as different books they&rsquo;re reading. Bill likes G. K. Chesterton, while Nick prefers Hugh Walpole. They also discuss baseball; apparently, the two of them are both fans of the St. Louis Cardinals, but Nick thinks that some of the games they lose are rigged, claiming &ldquo;There&rsquo;s always more to it than we know about.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Throughout the night, they continue to drink and add logs to the fire. The topic of conversation moves onto their fathers and their differing occupations. Nick&rsquo;s dad is a doctor, while Bill&rsquo;s is a painter. Nick thinks his dad has missed very much because he has never drank, Bill says that &ldquo;Everything&rsquo;s got its compensations.&rdquo; The two also discuss what makes a drinker a drunkard.</p>\r\n<p>During one scene, Nick goes into the kitchen to get more water, and while he&rsquo;s there he passes a mirror. He smiles and winks at his reflection that &ldquo;was not his face.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Finally, after many drinks, Bill brings up an incident from the past. He tells Nick that he was &ldquo;very wise&rdquo; for not marrying Marge, assumingly a previous girlfriend of Nick&rsquo;s. Bill gives several reasons why it was a good decision, while Nick just sits and listens and doesn&rsquo;t reply. At first it seems to bother Nick a lot, claiming that everything was finished and gone and that he would never see her again.</p>\r\n<p>However, the two decide to &ldquo;get really drunk,&rdquo; and Nick seems to change his mind about the whole situation, claiming that he felt happy and that &ldquo;nothing was finished.&rdquo; He resolves to go to town on Saturday because &ldquo;there&rsquo;s always a chance.&rdquo;</p>','2014-05-29 14:17:52',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(24,'Unchopping a Tree','<p><strong>Is unchopping a tree Possible? What does the essay suggest about conservation and against deforestation?</strong></p>\r\n<p>W.s Merwin shows us the real beauty of nature and the lesson gives us different meaning then it actually tells to save the environment, The task discussed in the essay is impossible i.e. Unchopping a tree is not possible. The whole idea falls to a single conclusion I,e, &ldquo; If you can&rsquo;t undo certain thing, then don&rsquo;t do it.&rdquo;<br />The writer is giving directions to unchop a tree. He wants to bring back the nature. Unchopping a tree actually is not possible. Even after all the branches twigs, leaves, Saw dust, bark have been jept in place, it is not possible to set the sap flowing, Once dead you cannot bring it back by any means. The essaist shows us the real beauty of nature. We cannot obtain that beauty by any artificial means. How the leaves stick to the branches and life flow in the tree?If ew cannot make that happen then why do we destroy them?<br />The writer doesn&rsquo;t want anyone to destroy nature which is stronger than us.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What does the essay \"Unchopping a tree\" suggest about conservation?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Ans: The essay \" unchopping a tree\" by showing the impossibility of restoring once cut down trees, makes people aware of the fact that we should not destroy the natural forest indiscriminately. Even if by hook or crook, you are able to make the tree stand, you can\'t infuse life on it. It is easy to chop but impossible to restore. Thus before we chop we must know how to unchop, which is impossible. To sum up, he warns us against deforestation. If the acts are not stopped on time, it is going to boomerang on us in the long run.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:20:19',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(25,'Keeping Things Whole','<p><strong>Intercept the Poem in any way you like?</strong><br />&ldquo;Keeping Things whole&rdquo; By Mark Strand is a plead for wholeness against the usual fragmentation that goes on on life. This poem talks about alienations, treating darkness and doubleness of man. This whole poem is the writer&rsquo;s quest to find his identity and wholeness in life.<br />Life is a journey, it is continuous. IT never stops. The poem in this essay is also travelling the same journey, He is trying to find his missing identity in his life, In a field, he stands and sees but he is still absent there, That is because he doesn&rsquo;t belong there, The poet&rsquo;s case is same everywhere. Whenever he goes he is always missing. The poet journey to find wholeness but all he see so he work is more fragmentation, He part the air as he walk and his space is soon replaced. That is because he has done nothing significant in his life. So when he looks back at his past himself, he doesn&rsquo;t find anyone. His space is already taken. So, he moves on and on to find himself to give meaning to his life and have a special remembrance.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Write the central idea of the poem.</strong><br />Ans: We human beings move from one place to another place to fulfill our purpose. We all have our own purposes for moving. When we move from one place to another place, we divide the air but the air moves in to fulfill the place from where we have gone through. Similarly we become absent in the place which we leave. According to the poet this happiness all the time in our life, we try to do wholeness/completeness but everything remains incomplete. When we solve one problem, other problems move in like air moves in. In the same way we find something missing in the first place when we go to another place.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:22:08',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(26,'Concrete Cat','<p><strong>Concrete Cat</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Dorthi Charles</p>\r\n<p>Concrete cat is a concrete poem. A concrete poem is an experimental poem, which verbally deals with visual ideas with an attempt to articulate visual thinking and bring the aesthetic principle of paintings into the poetry. It is mostly written to look at although it uses letters instead of painting brush.</p>\r\n<p>In &ldquo;Concrete Cat&rdquo; we can see Dorthi Charles has used black letters and placed it in such a manner that it shows us the picture of a cat on the page. To make the picture more vivid, he has used pointed letters. &ldquo;A&rdquo; shows the pointed ears of cat, the capital &ldquo;Y&rdquo; is used to show the wide opened eyes of cat as it is approaching food. The stripes, whiskers, mouth, paw and tail also made visible by appropriate arrangement of letters.</p>\r\n<p>The poet has also associated some catness with the concrete cat. For example a mouse is shown upside down. It means the cat has recently killed it, which is cat&rsquo;s nature. Similarly, the letter &ldquo;U&rdquo; is used mouth to suggest that a cat licks its food. There are some litter boxes at the corner, which suggests that the cat is in a storeroom. The food kept near it also suggests that the cat is a domestic one.</p>\r\n<p>The poet has also used a pun in the poem. A pun is a device of figurative language in which a word with two meanings is playfully used in a context. The punning words are spelled and pronounced in the same way. We find the mid stripe on the cat&rsquo;s body can be read as &ldquo;stripe&rdquo;, which means a long extended black line on a cat&rsquo;s body. At the same time it can also be read as &ldquo;tripes&rdquo;, which means the food inside its stomach.</p>','2014-05-29 14:24:10',5,1,NULL,5,1,0,0),(27,'Concrete Cat','<p><strong>Would you call this poem a work art?</strong><br />I think Concrete cat by Dorthi Charles is a poem of art. This poem doesn&rsquo;t have complicated lines or meaning but rather for eyes than it is for ears. Normally a poem is known for its hidden meaning but the poet has done something different in the poem and try to bring change in literature.</p>\r\n<p>We humans are creature of habits. We are bound in rule and as we follow the rules , we creae a habit out of it. The same goes to literature, The writers have a fixed pattern of writing and we find no significant difference in literature. But, Dorthi Charles have brought things that no writers thought of. The things that exist in our surrounding are shown in this kind of poem. The poet uses visual appearance on the page to create a poem, this kind of poem are rather Imaginative, More ever, the poet &ldquo;Dorthi Chales&rdquo; also used Pun in the poem like a usual traditions, Here Strip can be read as Stripe and tripes. Stripes are relatively long band or texture and tripers area stomach tissue of an animal used as a food or useless things. Also the language in the poem is reduced and simple.</p>\r\n<p>So, I would call this poem a work of art due to the different thought of the poet.</p>\r\n<div><strong>`Concrete Cat\' is an example of a concrete poem, how?&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div>Ans: This poem is made for eye. This poem doesn\'t concern much with emotions. The capitalized `A\' in ear is for pointed ear, \'Y\' for eyes, \'U\' for cat\'s mouth. Similarly the words `stripes\' is for stripes of the cat and `upside\' mouse indicates dead mouse and the cat killed it. The poem is very fully and humorous. The poet is successful to give the concrete structure of the cat with the help of individual letters and words.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:24:55',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(28,'Oops ! How\'s That Again','<p><strong>Oops! How&rsquo;s That Again</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-Roger Rosenblatt</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Different Type of error talked in the essay</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Slip &nbsp;of Tongue</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Verbal Error</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Fluffs</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Gaffes</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary</strong></p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Oops! How&rsquo;s That Again&rdquo; is an essay written by Rosenblatt and this essay has a humorous tone. Through the humorous tone also, the essayist has tried to reflect the bitter reality of human beings when they make mistake when they speak. He enriches his discussion with remarkable examples; although, as befits its subject. He is much concerned with the psychological causes of bloopers.</p>\r\n<p>Human beings often make mistake knowingly and unknowingly when they speak. After making mistake they also apologize for it. From the uneducated person to highly intellectual and educated, scholar, different mistakes are made according to their level. This essay describes the mistake the people make while speaking and the reasons behind it are divided into four categories. They are as follows: i. Public Blunders ii. Memorable Translations iii. Bloopers iv. Spoonerisms.</p>\r\n<p>Public Blunders are the mistakes made by the people when they give speech. While delivering the speech, they don&rsquo;t actually care for the grammatical mistakes or vocabulary mistakes. These mistakes are specially committed by especially by the political leaders when they deliver their speech. They try to give emphasis by giving different examples but their sentences are not totally complete. This happens due to their tongue slip. Here the speaker may be trying to give message from one view but the different audience may take it in wrong way.</p>\r\n<p>Memorable translations are the mistakes generally done by the people who speak very fast. This is also related to the psychological condition of the listener. The words spoken by the fast speaker may not be easily understood the real words. There may be misunderstanding between the speaker and listener. The person with weak psychology, if, wrongly interprets the words of the speaker, it may bring violent situation.</p>\r\n<p>Bloopers are the mistakes done foolishly and not tried to correct. These mistakes are very simple types of mistakes, which are not given much importance by the speaker. This may be the habit of some people. Spoonerisms are the mistakes, which are done by the use of incorrect words due to tongues slips. Here, wrong words are not known by the listener as the speaker immediately tries to replace the wrong word when he comes to know the mistake. While the replacement of words the speaker should be conscious as wrong replacement can misinterpret the actual meaning.</p>\r\n<p><br />There are different views about the verbal errors according to different people. Victoria Fromkin, a linguist, says that the verbal errors happen due to tongue slips concerned with the brain. Before the words are expressed, thought is placed by the brain into a grammatical framework. Sigmund Freud, a psychiatrist, presents his theory about the verbal error in different way. According to him, a tongue slips are caused by the network of id (unconscious mind), ego (subconscious mind) and superego (conscious mind). When people make mistakes, it has become the trend to laugh at them. Why do we laugh at them we don&rsquo;t know. According to the philosopher Henri Bergson, the act of laughter is caused by any interruption of normal human fluidity or momentum. So, tongue slips are like slips of banana peels. We simply make fun and hoot at the errors simply to break the monotonies.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:25:43',5,1,NULL,5,1,0,0),(29,'Oops ! How\'s That Again','<p><strong>1. Into what group has Rosenblatt organized his blunders example of verbal miss-steps?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Ans: Rosenblatt has organized them into four groups: public blunder, memorable mistranslations, bloopers and spoonerisms. First he talks about public blunders e.g. Nancy Regan describes the voters as \"The beautiful white people\" secondly, the writers say about memorable translation. This type of error is created when \"Come alive with Pepsi\" another verbal error is blooper is generally made on TV and radio programmes. In place of saying \"Herbert Hoover\" one says \"Boobert Heever\". The fourth error is \"Spoonerisms\" once Spooner said to his students. \"You have hissed all my mystery lectures\" instead of \"You have missed all my history lectures.\"</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>2. What explanation does Rosenblatt advice for the human tendency to make verbal errors?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Ans: The writer examines many reasons why the speaker makes such errors. According to the writer, slip of the tongue is the main cause of the mistakes (verbal errors). Slip of the tongue is like slip on the banana peels. The thoughts in our mind are put into the grammatical order before we express them. According to Freud, the slips or the verbal errors are caused by the speaker\'s inner desires. The tongue slips also because other types or verbal errors such as blooper (stupid mistakes) and spoonerism. The writer says that nothing is perfect and ever successful. It is human nature to make mistakes.</p>','2014-05-29 14:26:37',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(30,'Malini','<p><strong>Malini</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-Rabindranath Tagore</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Character</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">King</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Prince&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Supriya</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Kemankar</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Brahmins</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Queen</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Malini - Princess</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Theme</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Love and Hatred</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary</strong></p>\r\n<p>Rabindranath Tagore is a Bengali Indian poet, writer and philosopher. He was born is 1861 and died in Calcutta (now Kolkata). He is famous for his poetic works, philosophical plays, novels and short stories. The poetic play, Malini, is a story of love and hatred. It also deals with the topics such as religion, faith, friendship, devotion, sacrifice, forgiveness, loyalty, betrayal, etc.<br />&nbsp;<br />The play opens with the agitation of the Hindu Brahmins for the banishment of Malini, the princess of Kashi. A Hindu kingdom. Malini has been charged for her acceptance of a new creed, i.e. Buddhism. Having been taught by Buddhist Monks, she was influenced by Buddhism. She does not find any attachment with the worldly beauty and the material world. She thinks that wealth does not cling to whose destiny it is to find riches in poverty. Her mother, the Queen opines that for a woman, husband and children are the objects of worship.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />The king and the Queen are worried about her acceptance of Buddhism and request her to give up her new creed. The Queen believes Malini to be a pure flame of fire and thinks some divine spirit has taken birth in her but the king does not want her to take the burden of the world on her shoulders.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />Kemankar, a firm and determined youth, is the leader of agitators. Supriya, the childhood friend of Kemankar is also an agitator. Malini is charged as a poisonous snake who is aiming at the heart of Hindu religion. Supriya does not approve the idea to banish Malini in the name of religion. He knows that the truth cannot be determined by the force of numbers. He supports Malimi&rsquo;s belief that the love and truth as soul and body of all religions. Though the essence of all religions is same, Kemankar believes in their different forms. Supriya leaves the assembly assuring Kemankar about their friendship.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />All the agitators step back when they come to know that the army is in support of the agitation. They think it as a rebellion and extreme measure. They believe that their faith, not the arms, will give them victory. So make penance and invoke the goddess to descend from heaven to less and give power to them. Malini enters with all in the palace, and receives the honour of the ordinary citizens except Kemankar and Supriya. They ask for forgiveness, Malini announces her self exile and wants to make home renouncing the royal palace. Kemankar becomes alone in the agitation. So he makes a plan to go to the foreign land to bring soldiers to fight. Though Supriya does not like this plan, he wants to go with him for their friendship&rsquo;s sake. Kemankar orders him to remain there to watch and keep him informed.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />The first part of the play ends with the conversation about Malini. The king shows the determination to banish Malini as the demand persisted but he immediately changes his mood when he learns about Malini&rsquo;s missing. But Malini is brought back by the Brahmins and the soldiers with a great honour.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />The second part of the play opens in the garden where Malini and Supriya are talking. Supriya wants to be led by Malini but she does not think herself so great to lead him. During conversation Malini wants to learn about Kemankar from Supriya. He said that Kemankar&rsquo;s mind has always been firm and determined while his mind or thoughts are always flickering with doubts. Supriya suddenly reveals that he has deceived his friend by informing his plan to the king.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />The king enters. He is very much happy with Supriya and so he proposes Supriya to ask for anything even the princess Malini along with provinces worthy to tempt a king. But he refuses all. He thinks these as rewards for his treachery. He only wants love from Malini, which she has for every creature in the world.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />Kemankar has been captured by the king&rsquo;s soldiers and the king is going to execute him for his treason. Both Malini and Supriya plead the king to pardon him. He is brought before the king who wishes to meet Supriya. Since he wants to know why Supriya has done that or why he betrayed his own friend. Supriya replies he did to keep faith. He blames Supriya being a faithless. Supriya replies that true faith is there is love, where there is man. He says he got the knowledge from malini, which he could not get from any sacred books. Supriya wants to make compromise but Kemankar says falsehood and truth cannot live side by side in friendship.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />Supriya assures Kemnakar that he is paying his life for his love as Kemankar knows for the faith. At this Kemankar wants them to be judged in front of the death. Then Kemankar strikes Supriya with his chains and Supriya falls and he dies. Kemankar calls for his executioner but Malini requests the king to forgive him.<br />&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:27:43',5,1,NULL,5,1,0,0),(31,'Malini','<p><strong>1. Would you call Supriya a betrayer? Give reasons for your answer.&nbsp;</strong><br />Ans: Yes, we can say Supriya as a betrayer because Supriya and Kemankar were two close friends. They used to stay together. Kemankar wanted to go to foreign land &nbsp;to bring armies to revolt against Malini. Supriya also wanted to go with Kemankar. Kemankar asked him to retain there and inform him. While Kemankar was in foreign land, he warns Supriya not to betray their old friendship because of the new religion. But Kemankar goes to foreign land and writes his friend about plans then Supriya informs about Kemanker\'s secret plan to the king. King captures Kemankar. In this way, Supriya can be said as a great betrayer. He actually deceived his own close friend.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>2.If the demand persisted, would the king banish his Daughter? Give Reasons</strong><br />Yes, I think if the demand was persisted the king would banish his daughter. Malini, Rabindranath Tagore, is a story of love and hatred. Love is shown in its pure form but it also show love in its petty selfishness. This Story (play) also shows us that one&rsquo;s religion is grater by its own way. Religious Tolerance and love is the Secret to Success.</p>\r\n<p>Here, Malini Have changes to Buddhism. But the Brahmins are not happy. Hence, they have asked for banishment of malaini. The king is the reprensitive of people. He should do what other wants, majority decides. So, if only to make the citizen happy, he would have vanished Malini. Malini herself aslo asked for her Banishment. Also the prince himself wants Malini Vanished as soon as possible.<br />Hence, Since all of points are supporting banishment of MAlini. Therefore the king would have banished Malini if the revolt continued.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3.Draw a Character Sketch of Supriya and Show how he is different from kemankar?</strong><br />Supriya is grey Character in the Play. His character is changing from Brahmin to Malaini. He is very supportive of his friend and is broad minded. He took other religion and believed in religious tolerance. He was Very practical minded in this way. He follows his heart as he supported Malini. But he is very fickle minded. Once he is supporting Kemankar the next he is supporting Malaini.<br />Unlike, SUpriya Kemnekar is strong headed. He blindly supported his religion, and this failed him to see tolerance between the two religions. He believed too much in his religion and bolls. He was not so practical minded. He was revengeful and competitive. This is what led him to kill supriya. He wanted war and no other religion to progress.</p>\r\n<p><strong>4.What was the revolt against? Against Malini? Against the king? Against Buddhism?</strong><br />Malini, by Rabindra Nath Tagore is a story of love and hatred. Love in its pure form but it also shows how petty selfishness is ruling the world with hatred, here, Malini changes her religion and a revolt have started.</p>\r\n<p>The revolt may seem to be against Malini but the truth is the revolt is against Buddhism. Here, the Brahmins are revolting not because Malini have done anything wrong but they fear their own religion would vanish if they left some other religion grow. Due to this fear they dint want religious tolerance. <br />Hence, the revolt is against all Buddhism.</p>\r\n<p><strong>5.Would you call Supriya a betrayer? Give your answer.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Supriya is shown as a grey character in the story. So, it is not clear whose side he is in. He is not so strong headed and his mind keeps changing i.e. he is fickle minded. But, supriya can be called a betrayer even though he prevented war.</p>\r\n<p>The false hope he gave to his friend his lack of determination is the main cause of him being a betrayer. He could support whomever he wanted. He could go support kemanker or Malini, but he should have made clear to his friend whose side he was on. Since, he made false promises telling he would wait, he betrayed Kemamkar.<br />Hence, I would call Supriya a betrayal due to false promise.</p>','2014-05-29 14:28:21',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(33,'A Worn Path','<p><strong>Trace the various obstacles old Phoenix comes is against between the valley where we first pick her up and the wagon track, and describes how she deals with each.</strong><br />For her old age, the journey itself was an obstacle for old PhonieX Jackson. The first obstacle she comes through is the high hills. She climbs the hill gently but her dress gets caught in the thorny bush. She became busy and intent in the bush to free her skirt. Finally, she managed to get free. But, then she has to cross the log by putting her right foot out, leveling her cane fiercely before her, she marched across. Then, came the barbed wire fence where she had to creep and crawl spreading her knees and stretching her fingers like a baby trying to climb the steps. After that she had to pass through corn field. Then, she comes in contact with a scary crow, who she accidently thought a ghost. Then she came face to face with a black dog. She went in the ditch like a little puff of milk-weed trying to chase the dog away. A white-hunter helped her up.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>In Egyptian Mythology the Phoenix was a bird of great splendor that every five hundred years consumed itself by fire and rose renewed from its own ashes. In what way is Phoenix Jackson like the Bird?</strong><br />The name Phoenix, itself tells us something about Phoenix Jackson. Just like the bird, Phoenix Jackson also went through different phases of life. She was by no mean a well-to-do kind of lady but still she lived a long life. The bird Phoenix also has a long life of five hundred years. Every five hundred years interval later, the bird burns itself and again rise renewed from its own ashes, Phoenix Jackson also make a journey to the town in regular interval and gives life to her grandson. The Phoenix bird and Phoenix both have fought for their survival. They both are one of a kind. There is no such bird as Phoenix and nobody can be as daring and lovely as Phoenix Jackson. They both refuse to give up. Even at the old age, she makes the journey to the town. Both of them have collected a lot of experiences in their life time due to which both of them are fearless.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-05-29 14:30:18',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(42,'Aromatic Hydrocarbon','<p>1. &ldquo;Benzene is an aromatic compound&rdquo;. Justify on the basis of Huckel&rsquo;s rule.</p>','2014-06-03 11:44:32',8,2,NULL,2,3,0,0),(43,'Haloalkanes and Haloarenes','<p>1.&nbsp;Why is chloroform stored in airtight dark brown bottle?</p>\r\n<p>2. How would you convert chlorobenzene into</p>\r\n<p>a. DDT b. Toluene</p>\r\n<p>3. Why is nucleophilic substitution reaction in cholorobenzene difficult as&nbsp;compared to ethylchloride.</p>\r\n<p>4. How is pure trichloromethane prepared in lab? How does it react with acetone?</p>','2014-06-03 11:46:32',8,2,NULL,2,3,0,0),(44,'Alcohols and Phenols','<ol>\r\n<li>Why is phenol more acidic than aliphatic alcohol?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;How is phenol prepared from &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; a. Aniline&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; b. benzene&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; c. Phenyl magnesium bromide&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Write short note &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; Victor Meyer&rsquo;s method for the distinction of 1<sup>0</sup>, 2<sup>0</sup> and 3<sup>0 </sup>alcohol.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>','2014-06-03 11:57:18',8,2,NULL,2,3,0,0),(45,'Look at The Tea cup','<p><strong>Look at The Tea Cup</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Patricia Hampl</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Issues discussed in the essay</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">1) Difference between traditional norms and modern ideology</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">2) Disaster caused by second world war</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">3) Generation gap</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">4) changed value of marriage</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">5) Plight of woman</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">6) men- women relationship</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary</strong></p>\r\n<div>The essay &lsquo;Look At A Teacup&rsquo;, written by Patricia Hampel, shows how a simple writing helps in finding out great events. It is about the history of writer&rsquo;s mother in a delicate teacup. The two major themes of this essay are relationship between a mother and her daughter and a connection between the past generation and present generation. Both these things are represented by a teacup.</div>\r\n<div>The writer&rsquo;s mother was married in the year 1939, the beginning of the Second&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_7\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">World War</span>. The same year she bought the teacups as gifts that were later given to the daughter. Hampel sees a connection between herself and her mother. The teacup reminds her of her mother&rsquo;s history because her mother bought it in<a name=\"more\"></a>&nbsp;1939. Through the cup the mother&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_8\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">transfers</span>&nbsp;the<span id=\"mm11z93r68_2\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">culture and history</span>&nbsp;of her time to the daughter. So, the cup is historical memory only. It was made in Czechoslovakia, which was taken over and destroyed by the armies of Adolf Hitler.</div>\r\n<div>The essay associates and removes the objective description and subjective feeling of author and teacup. The author can express lots of feeling and&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_4\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">ideas making</span>&nbsp;the teacup as a medium. She tries to compare the falling of flower in the teacup as destruction of beauty due to falling bombs. There was also cultural and social degradation. The style of this essay is&nbsp;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_3\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">stream of consciousness</span>. So, the reader feels somehow puzzled to track down the plot of the essay. She expresses all her feelings try to compete each other. So, some sentences are fragmented. Logically they do not follow each other. The writing is beautifully decorated but the meanings are deviated.</div>\r\n<div>There is symbolic meaning of the things. &lsquo;<span id=\"mm11z93r68_5\" class=\"mm11z93r68\">Falling flowers</span>&rsquo; implies the degrading situation and &lsquo;teacups&rsquo; were human rituals and arts. Certainly the essayist refers the fall and break of culture. &lsquo;Falling bodies&rsquo; were dying people in the war and &lsquo;beds&rsquo; have meaning of the battlefield where the falling bodies lay. &lsquo;The falling of bombs onto women&rsquo; means the tragic fate of these women. They had the disturbed married life. Fates of women were accursed by the war and their destiny was darkened by the war and their destiny. &lsquo;Falling countries&rsquo; refers to the degradation of humanity, peace, progress, brotherhood, culture, etc. of the countries involved in the war. This essay presents the reality of war and shows the real picture of the world caused by the destruction due to war.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Things that fell in 1939</strong></div>\r\n<div>country</div>\r\n<div>art</div>\r\n<div>development</div>\r\n<div>civilization</div>\r\n<div>dead bodies</div>\r\n<div>bodies of bride in bed</div>\r\n<div>tradition</div>\r\n<div>dreams and hope</div>\r\n<div>faith in marriage</div>\r\n<div>humanity</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>','2014-06-03 12:42:23',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(35,'Look at the Teacup','<p>Excercise</p>\n<p><strong>Expalin &ldquo;The cup is a detail, a small unchatted finger from mid-cenyury bonfire.&rdquo;</strong><br /> &ldquo;The cup is a detail, a small unchatted finger from mid-cenyury bonfire&rdquo;. The cup in the sentence refers to the cup bought by thr writer&rsquo;s mother in 1939 which was a souviner handed to her, The Tea cup was thin, palest water green imaginable. Sometimes, in certain lights it is so pale, it doesn&rsquo;t seem green at all.It is shiny, and there are thin bands of gold cup and again midway down th bowl of the cup and it&rsquo;s base, which is subtly formed into a semi-pedestal. There is also a band of gold on the inner circle of the saucer,but it has been worn away after so many years of use. Inside the cup there are flowers, as if some one has scattered a bouquet and it had tumbled into seperate blossoms, falling in a full circke around the inside.Some had already fallen wheras some were still falling.No flowers in the cup were simillar.<br /> <br />The cup was one part of the history not beacuse it was too old but it had lived through the destruction cauesd by Second Wolrd war. Many and many things fell that yeat but the cup was still safe. In other way, the cup was safe because someone had looked after it. Here,the easiest wants to imply that the second world war could also had been avoided had they taken good steps. Bodies fell in Europe but the tea cup had no scratch on it. The second world war was the most devasting war of man kind, Many inncocent, were killed and Billions of worth Property were destroyed.And even in Barcelona, almost for the 1st time in history a woman carrying a bunch of Forsythia wrapped in waxed paper ran for cover,hidding from air.The newborns died without seeing what world had to offerm Many women wrere widowed and many childern were Orpahned. Humanity had also Died along with the war. So, this war brought down everything along with it.</p>\n<p>In short, the lines wants to say how we could have protected ourself or avoided the second world war by only taking good care of our own nation.</p>\n<p><strong>What do you mean by&rdquo; Many things fell that year&rdquo;?</strong><br />&ldquo;Many things fell that year&rdquo;. This line is reffereing to the year 1939, begginning of the seound world war. In 1939,everything fell. The flowers in the tea cup fell, This symbolically represent Bombs falling from the year adn some already landed taking thousands and thousand sof inncoents lives. Just like the flowers in tea cup, the bombs were landing, Many dead bodies have fallen that year.</p>\n<p>When there is a war,development also stops.once development stops, a country falls.In1939,the country fell,thery wew never upgraded again.Just like Czekoslovakia, the cup made were sold but the skill had alreaday fell.Our own human civilization which taught us our lessons and kindness fell. For the first time bodies of bride paired with other bodies fell on bed. Our Tradition and culture lesson fell.They proved to be wrong.All dreams and hopes one had for fututre fell due to the war only because one had to serve the country.Many women were widowed and many men were killed.This decreased the faith in marriage and finally faith in marriage fell. War had made men cruel and didnt care about anyone else . So, the greatest of all humanity fell that year.</p>\n<p>So, everything fell that year from falling of flowers to humanity.</p>\n<p>How does Hampel see herself and her mother connected by the tea cup?<br />Look at the tea cup is a essay that is completly depended upon the tea cup.Here the tea cup is the medium for all questioned asked in the essay.The tea cup was brought by Hampel mother in 1939.She preserved it and handed it to her daughter.</p>\n<p>The essay talks about the realtionships of mother and daughter.In this essay the mother is a silent kind of women. Whereas her daughter is a talkative one.The daughter wants to know many things about the past.But her mother sayd that there was no significant in her life.But the daughter didnt agree.Beacuse she had survived the war. At that time even europe started to eat itself raw.The daughter however thought her life was very significant due to it. The mother passed down the teacup as a soviner. This is where all the questions start to rise.The daughter looks at the cup and all the questions abut her mother past stars to come out.This cup has helped her to understand the life of her mother life better than ever before. She understood the life of women in 1939 because of her mother. The mother doesnt talk about her life.This shows the way a women wants to keep all her pain to herself.</p>\n<p>In short, the tea cup is where all the sumberged figure starts coming out and all the past connected to her mother comes out.</p>','2014-05-29 14:38:33',5,2,NULL,5,1,0,0),(38,'Metalic conduction','<p>Metallic condution</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Let us consider a metallic conductor of lenght \'\'l\" and cross-section area \"A\". Aconductor contains large number of free ellectron. These electrons move randomly, until the extrenal electric field is applied. When external electric field is applied. When external electric field is applied acroos the ends of a conductor, free electron start mmoving along the specific path. This motion of electrons in a fixed direction provides electric current in a conductor.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Let N be the total number of free electrons in a conductor. Also \"n\" be the number of electrons per unit volume.</p>\r\n<p>N=nV &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;.1</p>\r\n<p>N=nAl&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;..2</p>\r\n<p>As we know that current is the rate of flow of charge.</p>\r\n<p>Current(I) = charge/time&nbsp; =q/t</p>\r\n<p>I =</p>\r\n<p>I =</p>\r\n<p>I =</p>\r\n<p>I = nAve &hellip;&hellip;&hellip;.3</p>\r\n<p>Here, e = electronic charge = 1.6&times;10<sup>-19</sup>C and v = drift velocity</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Drift velocity = The average velocity of an electron in a conduction is know as drift velocity.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;v = l/t</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-06-02 13:05:02',7,1,NULL,6,3,0,0),(36,'Tissue Culture','<h4>Tissue Culture</h4>\r\n<p>The concept of tissue culture was 1<sup>st</sup> introduced by Haberlandt in 1902. The technique of tissue culture depends on cellular totipotency. It can be defined as &ldquo;Cultivation of isolated plants or plant parts (Cells, tissues or organs) in the aseptic container containing artificially prepared medium, under controlled environment.&rdquo; This method of propagation is also called <strong>micropropagation. </strong>In Nepal this technology was introduced by Suman Br. Rajbhandari in 1969 at Godawari, Lalitpur.</p>\r\n<h5>Process of tissue culture</h5>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The plants which is to be cultured are selected such selected plant parts are called explpants.</li>\r\n<li>These explants are collected and allowed to surface sterilization by chlorine water or 5% calcium hypochloride then washed with water.</li>\r\n<li>All the equipment and glassware should be sterilized by placing them on hot air oven at 160&deg;C to 180&deg;C for 2-4 hrs.</li>\r\n<li>A nutrient having appropriate ingredient of organic compounds,, inorganic compounds, hormones, enzymes, Vitamins etc. are prepared along with adjustment in the pH of&nbsp; nutrients&nbsp; about 5-6.</li>\r\n<li>Such prepared nutrients are kept in the sterilized glassware and whole setup is allowed to autoclaving at 120&deg;C for 15 minutes.</li>\r\n<li>After sterilization of media the explant is inoculated inside the glassware containing media which is clone in laminar air-flow cabinet.</li>\r\n<li>After inoculation the whole setup is placed inside the incubator and temperature was maintained to 25&deg;C to 27&deg;C.</li>\r\n<li>In this way series of media transfer for explant for regeneration of explant.</li>\r\n<li>After few days numerous plantlets are observed inside the glassware.</li>\r\n<li>These plantlets are taken out from the glass ware and placed in pot. These pots are placed in green house for strengthening.</li>\r\n<li>After hardening (strengthening) these plantlets are distributed to farmers or sown in the field.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h5>Types of Tissue culture</h5>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Callus culture<br /> Callus is an undifferentiated mass of cells which are developed in injured parts. Callus cells are used as explants and cultured under controlled environment. Then these callus cells produce numerous plantlets and each plantlet is developed into mature plant.</li>\r\n<li>Shoot Tip culture<br /> This method is applied in those plants which are unisexual or sterile. In this method the shoot tip or vegetative buds are used as explant and cultured under controlled environment. These shoot tips produces numerous plantlets and each plantlet develop into mature plant</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h5>Importance of Tissue culture</h5>\r\n<p>Tissue culture is an important and modern technology which can be applied in different field:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Application of tissue culture is very simple easiest and cheapest method which can be applied by any person.</li>\r\n<li>It helps in mass production in small area within short period of time.</li>\r\n<li>It improves the quality and quantity of plant products.</li>\r\n<li>It helps to produce new variety with desirable characters.</li>\r\n<li>It helps to increase the resistance power of plants of economic importance.</li>\r\n<li>It helps to produce disease free plants.</li>\r\n<li>It plays important role indirectly for industries as mass production of raw materials can be produced by using tissue culture.</li>\r\n<li>Since it is simple method, it can be carried out by many private and public sectors; NAST, NARC, GREAT, Nepal Biotech Nursery.</li>\r\n</ol>','2014-05-31 14:36:02',9,1,NULL,4,1,0,0),(37,'Speaking of Children','<p><strong>Speaking of Children</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">-Barbara Holland</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Theme</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Advantage of one children</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">-Disadvantage of multiple children</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Summary</strong></p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;Speaking of Children&rsquo; is an essay written by Barbara Holland which shows&nbsp;the numerous problems of those parents who have got more than one child. One child is inevitable for all parents but more than one is a headache in various way and the essayist tires to address such kind of problems in this essay. The<span id=\"lt1rzfy_8\" class=\"lt1rzfy\">precious moment</span>, happiness and the family bliss are somewhere lost when the parents have more than one child.<br /><br />Having plural children are not only problematic to the parents only but for the children themselves because they are deprived from the fundamental and natural right and some are even deprived from the&nbsp;<span id=\"lt1rzfy_7\" class=\"lt1rzfy\">balance diet</span>. For the sole desires, interest and happiness as well as privacy and peacefulness, many parents are facing critical problems. The parents should have to fulfill the each and every demands of the children and these all are almost impossible if thy have the plural children. Apart from that, having more than one child creates social, economic problems. The parents can manage good environment in the house if they have one child. You can brainwash the mind of the children. It may not create problem for you. But plural children nourish a counter-culture trend in the family.<br /><br />According to the essayist&rsquo;s opinion, it&rsquo;s very essential to a&nbsp;<span id=\"lt1rzfy_6\" class=\"lt1rzfy\">healthy marriage</span>&nbsp;that the wife should manage some quiet private time to chat with the husband, preferably when he gets home from work. They need peace and privacy just for half an hour. But in such a private and peaceful moment also your children are disturbing you. Sometimes they quarrel, sometimes they break off something and sometimes they interrupt the peaceful conversation between the couple.</p>\r\n<div><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></div>\r\n<div><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>OUTLINE OF ESSAY</strong></span></div>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Problems of having more than a child in a family. One child is outnumbered and easy to manage.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Plural children weaken the pleasure and peace in the family. The&nbsp;<span id=\"lt1rzfy_2\" class=\"lt1rzfy\">family life</span>can be disturbed by the plural children and the situation can be very worst.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Mutual understanding, co-operation, love and harmony are almost impossible.</li>\r\n<li>The parents become tired and they can unable to control the family and destructive situation comes in final. The children make the house untidy and dirty, break things and produce unwanted noise.</li>\r\n<li>The consequences of having plural children cause the&nbsp;<span id=\"lt1rzfy_4\" class=\"lt1rzfy\">adverse impact</span>&nbsp;in the family. The family status decrease day by day regarding social, economic and cultural factors.</li>\r\n<li>One child is appendage (addition, attachment) in a family. But more than one is the way of life or the adverse way of life.</li>\r\n<li>The peace and privacy in family is possible when the parents have one child, likewise the joy and jovial family life is there. The parents do not get an hour to talk separately.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>One child leads the parents to live in easy way but more than one makes them difficult to live with all their problems and difficulties.</li>\r\n<li>One child is easy for upbringing, educating and feeding. The child grows up in the perfect environment and gets all the facilities or can live by his all child-right.</li>\r\n<li>The writer also addresses the child-spacing; at least two children are manageable in the family. But her serious concern is for a single child. The writer faces the serious problems in the family because of the plural children.</li>\r\n<li>The family expenditure rises highly if the parents have more than one child and the parents should face the economic crisis.</li>\r\n</ol>','2014-05-31 14:37:17',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(41,'Chemical Bonding and Shape of Molecules','<p><strong>Some Important Questions</strong></p>\r\n<p>1. The bond angle at the central atom in NF3 is 103 whereas in BF is 120. Givereason.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-06-03 11:41:04',8,2,NULL,2,3,0,0),(39,'Laws of photoelectric effect','<p><strong>The Laws of Photo-Electric Emission</strong></p>\r\n<p>i)Photoelectric effect is a spontaneous process which is independent to the temperature but it depends on the nature of metal.</p>\r\n<p>ii) The number of electrons emitted per second is directly proportional to the intensity of the radiation.</p>\r\n<p>iii) The&nbsp;<strong>maximum kinetic energy</strong>&nbsp;of the electrons emitted&nbsp;<strong>increases with the frequency</strong>&nbsp;of the radiation.</p>\r\n<p>iv) There is a&nbsp;<strong>minimum frequency below which no emission occurs</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>A graph of K.E.<sub>max</sub>&nbsp;of photo-electrons against frequency of radiation has the following form.</p>\r\n<p>The minimum frequency for photo-electric emission is called the threshold frequency, f<sub>o</sub>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-06-02 13:16:38',7,1,NULL,6,3,0,0),(40,'Digestive System (Alimentary Canal)','<h3>Digestion</h3>\r\n<p>The process of breaking down of complex form of food into simple water soluble form that can be absorbed by the cell is called digestion.</p>\r\n<h3>Digestive system</h3>\r\n<p>The system which is responsible for intake of food, digestion, absorption, assimilation and ejection constitute a digestive system. It can be explained under following topic:</p>\r\n<h5>Alimentary canal</h5>\r\n<h5>Associated digestive glands</h5>\r\n<h5>Physiology of digestion</h5>\r\n<h4>Alimentary canal</h4>\r\n<p>Alimentary canal is a long tubular coiled structure of varying diameter starting from mouth to the anus. It is about 8-10 m in length and consists of following parts</p>\r\n<p>Mouth</p>\r\n<p>Pharynx</p>\r\n<p>Esophagus</p>\r\n<p>Stomach</p>\r\n<p>Small intestine</p>\r\n<p>Large intestine</p>\r\n<p>Anus&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Mouth</h4>\r\n<p>It is small transverse slit like aperture guarded by upper &amp; lower lips situated below nasal cavity. It is meant for ingestion (intake of food), mastication (chewing of food) and swallowing of food. It consists of Vestibule (a narrow slit like space in mouth) which is externally covered by lips and chicks and internally by gums and teeth; and Buccal cavity (a spacious chamber situated in between upper and lower jaw) which is lined by mucous membrane and consist of 3 main parts i.e. palate, tongue, teeth</p>\r\n<h4>Palate</h4>\r\n<p>It forms the roof of buccal cavity and separates it from the nasal cavity. The palate is divided into anterior hard palate and interior soft palate. Anterior hard palate with transverse ridge called Rugae keeps food in proper place during mastication. Posterior soft part is a smooth surface that helps in easy swallowing. Posterior end of soft palate hangs down as a small finger like muscular flap called Uvula. It closes the internal nares during swallowing of food.</p>\r\n<h4>Tongue</h4>\r\n<p>It is a large muscular highly mobile structure lying on the floor of buccal cavity. It is attached with the floor of mouth cavity by a fold of mucous membrane called frenulum. The dorsal surface of tongue is rough due to presence of papillae. Papillae are the small progections that encloses the taste bud. There are 3 types of papillae.</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fujiform papillae: These are smallest, thread like structure present on the anterior 2/3 portion of Tongue.</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fungiform papillae: These are numerous mushroom shaped structures present at the tip and lateral edge of tongue i.e.bar</p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Vallate papillae: These are largest but usually 8-12 in number and are arranged in inverted V shape at the base of tongue.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Function of tongue</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>To taste the nature of food.</li>\r\n<li>Mastication ( chewing)</li>\r\n<li>In making the speech (articulation)</li>\r\n<li>Swallowing of food (Deglutition)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Teeth</h4>\r\n<p>Teeth are embedded in both the jaws in man. There are 3 types of teeth; thecodont, diphyodont and heterodont.</p>\r\n<p>1) <strong>Bunodont:</strong> Adapted for mastication</p>\r\n<p>2) <strong>Thecodont:</strong> Embedded in jaw sockets or theca&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>3) <strong>Diphyodont:</strong> Having 2 sets of teeth; first set is called milk teeth or deciduous teeth which are later replaced by second set of permanent teeth.</p>\r\n<p>4) <strong>Heterodont</strong>: Set of four different shape and size of teeth</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;i. Incisor-&nbsp; with the crown ( biting)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ii. Canine- for tearing</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; iii. Premolar- mastication</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; iv. Molar- mastication</p>\r\n<p>Last molar or third molar teeth are called wisdom teeth (vestigial organ).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Structure of teeth</strong></p>\r\n<p>Each tooth comprise of crown, neck and root.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Crown</strong>: It is the exposed portion of tooth above gum. It is externally covered by hardest substance called Enamel which protects the . Beneath the Enamel, there is dentine (made of hard substance similar to bone) which is tough but not as tough as Enamel and can Decay.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Neck:</strong> It is narrow portion between crown and root and is surrounded by gum.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Root:</strong> It is embedded in jaw bone and holds the tooth securely in place. Each tooth is composed of pulp cavity in the center. Pulp cavity consists of nerve fibres, blood vessels, sensory cells and odontoblast. Dentine surrounds pulp cavity. Cement is a hard substance surrounding embedded part of dentine around the root that holds the tooth inside the socket.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Function of teeth</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>For mastication</li>\r\n<li>For speech production</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Pharynx</h4>\r\n<p>Pharynx is a wide opening situated behind the mouth. It is lined by mucous membrane. Its functions are to act as a common passage for air and food. It consists of 3 parts: Nasopharynx, oropharynx, Laryngopharynx.</p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Nasopharynx</strong></p>\r\n<p>The uppermost portion of pharynx communicating with nose through internal nares and with ear through Eustachian tube extends from mouth to the level of soft palate is called Nasopharynx.</p>\r\n<p><strong>2.Oropharynx</strong></p>\r\n<p>Mid portion of pharynx acting as a common passage for air from nose to trachea and food passing from buccal cavity to oesophagus extending from soft palate to 3<sup>rd</sup> cervical is called Oropharynx.</p>\r\n<p><strong>3.Laryngopharynx</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is the lowermost portion which leads into two tubes i.e gullet (good pipe) and glottis (wind pipe). In front of the glottis, there is a muscular flap called epiglottis which closes the glottis at the time of food swallow to avoid the food entering inside to trachea. It extends from third to sixth cervical</p>\r\n<h4>Oesophagus</h4>\r\n<p>It is a long narrow muscular tube of about 25 cm which connects pharynx to the stomach. Its wall is lined by stratified squamous and columnar epithelium containing mucous gland. It runs straight down through the neck behind and along the trachea. It curves upward before opening into the stomach which prevents the backflow of gastric juice or components from the stomach.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Function</strong></p>\r\n<p>Serves as a food passage by peristaltic movement of muscular wall.</p>\r\n<h4>&nbsp;Stomach</h4>\r\n<p>It is large, elastic muscular, J-shaped muscular sac situated on the left side of the abdominal cavity. It is the widest part of the alimentary canal. It is of 25-30 cm in length with capacity of 2 litres. Stomach is divided into 4 regions: Cardiac, Fundus, body and pyloric.</p>\r\n<p>The region of stomach which continues from oesophagus is called cardiac orifice and with duodenum at the pyloric orifice. The cardiac is the uppermost part which continues the oesophagus.</p>\r\n<p>The Fundus is dome shaped structure above the cardiac orifice and is generally filled with air or gas.</p>\r\n<p>The body is the main part in fundus and pylorus.</p>\r\n<p>Pylorus is the lowermost funnel shaped structure that continues to duodenum.</p>\r\n<p>The Cardiac and pyloric region are guarded by rings of muscle called Sphincter Muscle which prevents regurgitation (backflow of food).</p>\r\n<p>The inner wall of stomach bears numerous folds called gastric rugae which disappear when stomach is full. Internally, the stomach wall consist numerous gastric glands which pour the secretion into the gastric pit or lumen. The gastric glands consist of 3 types of cells: oxyntic, peptic and Mucus cell; secreting HCL, pepsin and mucus respectively thus forming the gastric juice.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Function</strong></p>\r\n<p>The food can remain in stomach for long period of time (3-4 hrs).</p>\r\n<p>It is temporary reservoir of food</p>\r\n<p>Churning of food</p>\r\n<p>Hydrolysis or semi digestion of food (proteins) to make chime.</p>\r\n<p>Absorption of some amount of food i.e. water, glucose, alcohol.</p>\r\n<p>Muscular action of stomach mixes the food with Gastric juice that makes food soft and helps the enzymes to act on it</p>\r\n<p>HCl destroys many micro-organisms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4>Small Intestine</h4>\r\n<p>It is long narrow, tubular and coiled structure about 6.5 metres long lying in abdominal cavity. It is divided into 3 parts: Duodenum, Jejunum and ileum.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Duodenum</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is C-shaped structure and 25cm in length and 2.5 cm in breadth. It consists of Brunner&rsquo;s gland and crypts of lieberkuhm.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Jejunum</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is narrow than duodenum measuring about 1.5-1.8 in length. It is more or less in similar to ileum in structure and function.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Ileum</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is the last part of the small intestine which is highly coiled about 3.5 m in length and lie within the inverted U-shaped limb of colon of large intestine.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Function of small intestine</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Complete digestion of food</li>\r\n<li>Absorption of nutrients</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4>Large intestine</h4>\r\n<p>It is wider and shorter than small intestine, measuring about 1.5-1.8 m in length. It is divided into caecum, colon and rectum.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Function of large intestine.</strong></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Absorption of water</li>\r\n<li>Secretion of mucous</li>\r\n<li>Elimination of undigested food</li>\r\n<li>Manufacture of vitamin K and B-complex</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4>Anus (Anal canal)</h4>\r\n<p>It is last muscular organ part of digestive canal measuring about 2 cm (or maximum 3.8 cm) in length.</p>','2014-06-02 22:04:32',9,1,NULL,4,1,0,0),(49,'Biotechnology-Application of Biology','<h4>Biotechnology</h4>\r\n<p>Biotechnology (in Greek, Bio=living &amp; Technology=method) was 1<sup>st</sup> introduced by Karl Ereka in 1917.</p>\r\n<p>Biotechnology is a modern science in which is maximum utilization of living things like algae, fungi, bacteria, and living parts of higher plants and animals (cell, tissue) in the manufacture of useful products for the benefit of mankind and other form of life.</p>\r\n<p>This technology is old as human civilization. The ancient people also knew about this technology as preparation of alcohol, curd, cheese, butter, churpi, Gundruk, etc. but they didn&rsquo;t know about cause of such fermented products. Nowadays it has been advanced rapidly in the field of biochemistry, microbiology, biomolecule, genetic engineering, tissue culture, etc. hence biotechnology can be used in different field in different ways.</p>\r\n<p>Application of biotechnology in the field of Agriculture,</p>\r\n<p>Application of biotechnology in the field of Medicine, &amp;</p>\r\n<p>Application of biotechnology in the field of Industry.</p>\r\n<h4>Application of biotechnology in the field of Agriculture</h4>\r\n<p>Biotechnology plays important role in the field of agriculture, floriculture, horticulture, forestry, etc. The main objectives of this technology in this field are</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Production of disease free plants.</li>\r\n<li>Improvise the quality and quantity of plant products, &amp;</li>\r\n<li>Production of new variety of plants having desirable characters.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These all factors gave benefit to mankind and other forms of life.</p>\r\n<h5>Significant application in this field</h5>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><em>Tissue culture</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>A modern technology, defined as a cultivation of isolated microorganisms (algae, fungi, bacteria) and parts of higher plants or animals (cell, tissue, organ) in the aseptic container containing artificially prepared medium under controlled environment.</p>\r\n<p>From this method we can produce numerous plantlets within short period of time in a small area. These plantlets are called clones. Then these clones are grown in different environment where they grow rapidly and give good production. Besides these, by this method we can produce off-seasonal plants so that vegetables &amp; fruits can be available throughout the year. It is very simple, easiest and cheapest method and can be applied in any season by any person. E.g.:- Potato, Banana, orchids</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li><em>Meristem culture for production of fisease free plant</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>As we know that meristemetic tissue are newly formed cells found in shoot and root apex. These meristematic tissues are used as explant. These meristematic tissues are cultured under controlled environment. It produces numerous healthy plantlets. Such plantlets are grown in open environment where they grow rapidly as healthy plants though their parent is diseased.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n<li><em>Production of resistance varieties</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>The resistance power of wild plant is more than cultivated plants. When such cultivated plant is crossed with wild plant then resistant gene of wild plant recombine&nbsp; with susceptible gene then the weak plant is changed into resistant plant which can survive in adverse climatic condition and defense against weeds, pathogens etc. In this way resistant veriety of cultivated plants can be increased. E.g.:- Triticum aestivum crossed with Aegilops species ( wild grass ).</p>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li><em>Protoplast culture for production of new variety with desirable characters</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Mixture of protoplasm of 2 different isolated plant cells when cultured under controlled environment, it produces new hybrid plant having desirable characters. Such method is called <strong>protoplast culture.</strong></p>\r\n<p>E.g. &nbsp; Tomato &nbsp; + &nbsp; Potato = &nbsp;Pomato</p>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n<li><em>Anther culture for production of androgenic or haploid plant</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Whole anther or microspores are used as explant. When such explant cultured under controlled environment produces numerous haploid and sterile plants called Androgeny. In such plant, mutation can be detected easily so it is important for research lab. Such androgeny can be diploid to fertile by treating with Colchicine.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n<li><em>preparation of bio-fertilizer</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Fertilizers like nitrogen fixing bacteria, decomposers which are cultured in large scale and used in the soil to increase the fertility of soil. Similarly, different kinds of plant (Azolla, Sesbania aculeate and leguminous plants) are used in green manure preparation are cultivated and which when used in land increase the fertility of soil.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"7\">\r\n<li><em>plant breeding and hybridization</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>By plant breeding and hybridization, new and better kinds are produced which are economically important and beneficial. For example:- in Rice; Japonoca type of rice in hilly region like Taichung-176 &amp; Indica type of rice in terai region like Mansuli-IR20; Wheat-RR20;</p>\r\n<ol start=\"8\">\r\n<li><em>Genetic engineering</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Important genes can be inoculated and harmful genes can be removed from the body in order to form new and better type of life. It is genetic engineering or gene therapy. By this method nitrogen fixing plants can be produced from non-nitrogen fixing plants by injecting nitrogen fixing genes.</p>\r\n<p><em>&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n<h4>Application of biotechnology in the field of Medicine</h4>\r\n<p>Biotechnology plays an important role in the field of medicine. It is used for the treatment of different serious in plants and animal &amp; human health case as prevention, diagnosis and care of diseases. Beside these, it can be also used in production of vitamins, enzymes and vaccines. So this technology is significant for medication.</p>\r\n<h5>Significant application in this field</h5>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><em>&nbsp;</em><em>Production of Antibodies</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>A</em>ntibody is a proteinous substance which is produced from lymphocytes of vertebrates. These antibodies increase the immunity power of the body against the pathogens and antigen produced by microorganisms. Such antibodies are manufactured by <strong>hybridoma cell culture (</strong><em>A </em>modern Bio-technology in which tumor cell and lymphocyte is cultured to produce large amount of antibodies).&nbsp; These antibodies are used as medicines and available in the market.</p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li><em>Production of Antibiotics</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>A</em>ntbiotics are the chemicals produced from dead or living organisms,used after injection, kills pathogens and neutralize the toxin produced by pathogens. This antibiotics are synthesized by biotechnology and used as medicines. E.g.:</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"239\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Antibiotics</em></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Produced from</em></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Treatment</em></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"239\">\r\n<p><em>Tyrothrycene</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Bacillus brevis</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Mouth and throat infection</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"239\">\r\n<p><em>BCG</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Bacilus Calmitte Guerin</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Tuberculosis (TB)</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"239\">\r\n<p><em>Streptomycene</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Streptomyces gresius</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>T</em><em>uberculosis (TB)</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"239\">\r\n<p><em>Penicillin</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Penicillium nolatum</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"238\">\r\n<p><em>Pneumonia</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n<li><em>Production of vaccines</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>A Vaccine is a chemical </em>produced from dead or living organisms,used after injection, kills pathogens and activates immunity producing cells to increase immunity power.</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Vaccine</em></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Produced from</em></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><strong><em>Treatment</em></strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Anti-rabies</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Rabid dog</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Rabies</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>BCG</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Bacillus Callmitte Guerin</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>TB</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Tetanus</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Serum of diseased person</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"254\">\r\n<p><em>Tetanus</em></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li><em>Production of hormones, enzymes, vitamins</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Biotechnologically produced biochemical in large scale, used as medicines;</p>\r\n<p>Insulin, produce in thyroid gland and pancreas of human body, controls sugar. By genetic engineering, such glands are taken out and hormones are cloned out by inoculating it with bacteria and used as medicine for treatment.</p>\r\n<p>Different types of enzymes like Somatotrophin (growth hormones), Amylase, peptidase, are synthesized by biotechnology and used as medical treatment for dwarfism and disorders.</p>\r\n<p><em>Vitamins are also equally important for proper growth of living body. They are required only in trace amount but plays vital roles. Vitamin A is extracted from Yeast, Vitamin B<sub>12 </sub>from Clustridium butylicum, and Vitamin E &amp; K from E. coli.</em></p>\r\n<ol start=\"5\">\r\n<li><em>Gene therapy</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>A gene is a small segment of DNA which determines only one character in organism. Important genes are inoculated &amp; unwanted genes are removed from the body for better state of body of an organism, such phenomenon is called Gene Therapy.</em></p>\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n<li><em>Diagnosis of disesase</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>A Biotechnology used for detection of serious diseases like cancer, AIDS, etc. by DNA test, ECG so that if detected in time the treatment can be done; such process is called Diagnosis of diseases.</em></p>\r\n<h4>Application of biotechnology in the field of Industry</h4>\r\n<p>Biotechnology plays important role in industrial aspects like manufacture, generation etc.</p>\r\n<h4>Significant application in this field</h4>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><em>Production of food materials</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>An industry produces agricultural products like rice, wheat, maize etc are made ready for eating like noodles, biscuits etc. Mainly there are beverage industries (production of beverages like wine, brandy, rum, beer, whisky), bakery (cakes, burger, breads) and Dairy (Cheese, butter, curd).</em></p>\r\n<ol start=\"2\">\r\n<li><em>Production of biogas</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Biogas is important for cooking and other purposes as fuel. Biogas is manufactured by the industrial technology from the ancient bacteria. Methanogenic bacteria which produce methane gas during anaerobic respiration. Beside these, it can be produced biogas from cow dung, field residue etc.</em></p>\r\n<ol start=\"3\">\r\n<li><em>Sewage disposal</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>This technology manufacture different kinds of decomposers as algae, fungi, bacteria which can be used in decomposition of sewage disposal where such microorganism convert complex organic substance into simple soluble manure such manure are reused in the field to increase fertility of soil.</em></p>\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n<li><em>P</em><em>roduction of organic acid</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Some important organic acid can be prepared by this technology as:</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Aspergillus nigar &ndash; citric acid</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Lactobacillus &ndash; lactic acid</em></p>','2014-06-03 22:29:08',9,1,NULL,4,1,0,0),(50,'The Six Million Dollar Man','<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>The Six Million Dollar Man</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Harold J. Morowitz</p>\r\n<div><br />\r\n<div>Dr. Harold J Morowita is a professor of Molecular Biophysics and Biochemistry. He is a scientist, teacher, and author. &lsquo;The Six Million Dollar Man&rsquo; is a popular essay in which Morowitz examines the statistical statement that the chemical value of the human body is only 97 cents. He spends his essay in refining and improving the statement and tries to arrive at a more accurate definition at the end.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>From a biochemical catalogue he collects the information about the price of ingredients that the human body is made of. Then he calculates the average value of a gram dry weight of human being and his own dry weight. When he multiplies both, he finds his price, i.e. Six million dollar. But soon he realizes that each human being is priceless and infinitely precious. He concludes his essay with Alfred North Whiteheads conclusion that &ldquo; the human body is an instrument for the production at art in the life of the human soul.&rdquo;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The author received a humorous birthday and from his daughter and son-in-law with a caption &ldquo; According to BIOCHEMISTS the materials that make up the HUMAN BODY are only worth 190 cents.&rdquo; The definition compelled him to make thorough study of the entire matter. He started by sitting down with his catalogue from a biochemical company and began to list the ingredients and their prices. His biochemical value was 97c when he was paying for the informally poorest form of cool, air, water, lime, bulk iron, etc. but in the six million dollar figure he was paying for his atoms in the highest informational state in which they are commercially available.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>It can be done for less than six thousand trillion dollars. But we cannot evaluate the human life in biochemical point of view. An incubator can develop micro-organisms artificially but it cannot assemble the cells into tissues, tissues into organs, and organs into a person, fill it with life and make a human being.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Thus, each human being is priceless and infinitely precious. We cannot evaluate a person&rsquo;s life in terms of money. The rationality and humanity are the characteristics of human being. It can produce anything. Alfred North Whitehead is true that &ldquo; The human body is an instrument for the production of art in the life of human soul.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Morowitz shifts his subject. He starts out talking about the human body and ends up talking about the human being. Human body and human being differ from each other. Human body is made up of chemical organism but a man becomes human being because of consciousness, rationality and some indispensable human qualities.</div>\r\n</div>','2014-06-05 12:59:37',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(51,'On the vanity of Earthly Greatness','<p><strong>On the vanity of Earthly Greatness</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Arthur Guiterman</p>\r\n<p><strong>Message of the poem:</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Time is the most valuable wealth and all our earthly greatness / achievements are useless in comparison with time. Time is the leader which can make a sage the King and the King a sage. So, we shouldn&rsquo;t be proud of earthly &nbsp;greatness as we have.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;On the Vanity of Worldly Things&rdquo; is a poem written by Arthur Guiterman, an American poet and journalist, is best known for his humorous verse. Through humour, he has tried to depict the reality of human beings and animals caused by the change in time. It shows the bitter reality that the power of animals or human beings doesn&rsquo;t remain same when time and situation change. We always run after reputation and prestige. We become or want to be great and we think it will remain the same forever. We earn reputation and prestige and we think it will remain the same forever. We earn reputation and we think that the credit won&rsquo;t be lost but actually we won&rsquo;t think that is destroyed in due course of time. Our greatness is dismissed by time. So, time laughs at our blindness and pride.</p>\r\n<p>Time is such a thing on which we cannot get victory. The nature has given us limited time to live and exercise our power. Beyond that time, we cannot move according to our desire. Only in favourable time and situation we can perform our actions or activities.</p>\r\n<p>The &ldquo;vanity&rdquo; actually means the degrading value of reputations of any persons and animals in the world. To clarify this point the writer has presented few examples. Julius Caesar was a great warrior and a famous general statesman. He earned a great name and fame in his time through his strength and power. But that power lost its value with the change in the time and situation. He does not posses any arm and power to show his power of the past. His head is on the shelf and weapons and other things belongings are only in the museum in the form of history.</p>\r\n<p>The roman emperor Charlemagne was a great in his time by his sword, power. But the power of his sword also became meaningless due to the change in time. Now that sword has been rusted and is kept useless in the museum. Not only the great kings and warriors, but there is also good presentation of powerful animals whose value has been decreased. Grizzly bear, whose embrace was very dreadful, has become nothing more than a rug to give warmth. Tusks of mighty brawls of mastodons have been changed into playing things like billiard balls.</p>\r\n<p>All the given examples are concerned with the greatness but the greatness has been turned and reduced to valueless things. The vanity human greatness and animals&rsquo; strength have become a good subject to present irony. That irony makes one feel unwell and quite indifferent to the person.Everybody becomes great in his time and situation but later on he becomes helpless and valueless. All reputation and achievements will be dismissed quickly. So, it is useless to take pride in one&rsquo;s power as everything decays and fades away in due course of time.</p>','2014-06-05 13:39:01',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(52,'In Bed','<p><strong>In Bed</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Joan Didion</p>\r\n<p><strong>Medical Background of Migraine:</strong><strong>Migraine</strong>: <br />&nbsp;[extremely bad headache] a recurrent, throbbing, very painful headache,often affecting one side of the head and sometimes accompanied by vomiting or by distinct warning signs including visual disturbances.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Symptoms of Migraine Headache:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Headache is not continuous if it occurs it lasts long.</li>\r\n<li>Migraine attack occurs almost four to five times in a month.</li>\r\n<li>Flush (blush or redness) of blood in cerebral / brainy arteries / blood vessels.</li>\r\n<li>Vision is not clear (temporarily blind)</li>\r\n<li>Mild hallucinations / false sense perceptions / illusion / nightmare</li>\r\n<li>Gastrointestinal / stomach / digestive / gastric disturbance</li>\r\n<li>Overpowering fatigue / exhaustion, tiredness, weariness, weakness, lethargy, etc.</li>\r\n<li>Aphasia / lack of language abilities</li>\r\n<li>Chilling / sweating</li>\r\n<li>Nausea / sickness of the stomach / the unsettling feeling in the stomach that accompanies the urge to vomit</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong>Causes of Migraine Headache Attack:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stress</li>\r\n<li>Allergy</li>\r\n<li>Fatigue</li>\r\n<li>Abrupt Change in atmosphere</li>\r\n<li>Flashing Light</li>\r\n<li>Decrease of serotonin (neurotransmitter chemical) in blood</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><br /><strong>Difference of Headache and Migraine Headache:</strong>(&nbsp;Common Headache:Aura: )&nbsp;a distinctive sensation or visual disturbance that may signal the beginning of a migraine headache</p>\r\n<p><strong>Aura Period:</strong>&nbsp;the period in which symptoms are seen as follows:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It has no symptoms in aura period.</li>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s not disease and can be cured or treated.</li>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s not physiological (body&rsquo;s internal processes)error.</li>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s not hereditary error.</li>\r\n<li>Ordinary headache</li>\r\n<li>It has no aura period.</li>\r\n<li>Pain killer works.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br /><strong>&nbsp;Migraine Headache:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It has symptoms in aura period of 15 to 20 minutes.</li>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s disease and can&rsquo;t be cured.</li>\r\n<li>Migraine is a physiological error.</li>\r\n<li>Migraine headache is hereditary error.</li>\r\n<li>Migraine is chemical disturbance in serotonin hormone which is in brain.</li>\r\n<li>It has aura period.</li>\r\n<li>Pain killer doesn&rsquo;t work.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The writer has chills, sweating, nausea, debility / weakness in her migraine headache.Non migraine patients think that the migraine patients are acting in the name of headache. They think that the headache can be cured by taking painkillers but in fact no painkillers act for migraine headache.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Summary:</strong></p>\r\n<p>&lsquo;In Bed&rsquo;, an essay by Joan Didion depicts her personal experiences with migraine headache, which she inherits from her parents. She presents something unusual about the disease in a more philosophical and meditative domain of thought.</p>\r\n<p>Joan spends her day in bed there almost five times a month because of the migraine headache. She knows that she is going to be attacked by the headache when she feels some sort of irritation and flow of blood in the vessels of her brain. To avoid the attack she takes some medicines and starts to work. In her earlier days, she thought that she would get rid of the disease just by denying it. Sometimes she even tells lies saying that she did not have the attack frequently. But the truth was that sometimes the attack was quite violent and long lasting. However, she feels good that she does not have any other physical problems, such as brain tumor, eyestrain or high blood pressure. She also tries to do all her normal work in spite of it. During the attack her right temple (head) would suffer extreme pain and tears would roll down from her right eyes. She would also vomit. Generally the headache may also be caused by stress, allergy, and tiredness, an abrupt change in blood pressure, a flashing light or a fire drill.</p>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s strange that no medicine works effectively in case of migraine, especially when the attack begins. Some people may have hallucination, blinding effect, stomach problem, tiredness and pain in all the senses along with headache. They are even unable to do their normal work. During the attack Didion can&rsquo;t see and speak clearly. She looks as if she has drunk some wine. But the headache never takes anyone&rsquo;s life. It is interesting to know what doctors believe about a migraine sufferer. They said that the individual is ambitious, inward, and intolerance of unbearable pain But Didion&rsquo;s untidy hair and carelessness in house keeping do not point out her migraine quality. However her great effort to write and rewrite a single paragraph for a week reveals some sort of perfection. Finally she accepts the diseases and lives with it. When she has it she simply concentrates on the pain. But after ten or twelve hours she gets some sort of refreshment and spiritual power. She opens the window and feels the air, eats gratefully and sleeps well. She feels as if she is blessed by God. Therefore she is happy.</p>','2014-06-05 13:51:27',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(53,'The Gardener','<p><strong>The Gardener</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Rudyard Kipling</p>\r\n<p>Rudyard Kipling (1865-1936), a British poet, novelist, and the writer of short stories was born in India and set many of his writings in the Indian flavor. He was awarded by the Nobel Prize for literature in 1907.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&lsquo;The Gardener&rsquo; ends surprisingly revealing the reality of Helen, the protagonist, and her relationship with Michael. Michael, whom Helen calls nephew, is in reality, her son whose father is unknown throughout the story. The gardener is a mysterious character who does not appear at first and in the middle but only at the last of the story creating confusions in the readers.</p>\r\n<p>Helen Turrell conceals (hides) the truth about Michael till the end of the story but she does not show any reaction when the gardener confidently says he will tell where her son lies.&nbsp;The villagers of Hampshire believe Michael to be an unfortunate son of Helen&rsquo;s late brother, George Turrell and his beloved (not wife). Actually it was not so. She had created a false story about Michael&rsquo;s parents. Michael was born when Helen was in southern part of France. She had told lies about her trip that she had long troubles. Because of the fear of social stigma she had told another lie that she had arranged for the passage of the child and a nurse from Bombay. She was thirty-five when she gave birth to the child. She showed much fondness to the child despite the fact that she was not the child lover.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Michael was fearless, Philosophical, and fairly good-looking. At the age of six, he knew that Helen was not her real mother but his aunt. She did not allow Michael to say her mummy because she was unmarried. To escape from the society&rsquo;s contempt, she made Michael know the false reality.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Michael got maturity in due course of time but his interest in Helen was constant and increasing throughout. Though Helen wanted him to go to Oxford University, he took war as his career. The First World War was going on. Many soldiers were killed during war. Michael was killed by the shell-splinter explosion. After getting full proof about his death, Helen, being a next of &ndash;kin, prepared to go and see his grave in Hazenzeelein the third Military Cemetery with perfect information.</p>\r\n<p>In a teashop, three kilometers away from cemetery, she met an English Woman, Mrs. Scarsworth. They stopped in a hotel where Mrs. Scarsworth revealed that she had come there to see the grave of someone special to her and also that she was unmarried. Helen told lie that she had come to see her nephew&rsquo;s grave.</p>\r\n<p>Next morning she walked alone towards the grave. As she was searching at the mean time she saw a man knelt behind a line of headstones-evidently a gardener. He did not introduce with her neither did he salute her. He asked her who she was looking for. She said it was Lieutenant Michael Turrell, her nephew. He had finite compassion in his expression and eyes. He said he would show her where her &lsquo;son&rsquo; lay. She went away, supposing him to be the gardener when she left the cemetery.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-06-05 13:54:47',5,1,NULL,2,1,0,0),(54,'Green Manure And Fertilizer','<p>Plants need different kinds of elements for natural growth such elements are taken by the plant from the soil but constant use of agricultural land &amp; harvesting of crop decrease the fertility of soil in such condition artificially prepared nutrients used in the soil for increasing the fertility of soil. Such nutrient is called fertilizer. It is 3 types.</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Organic fertilizer</li>\r\n<li>Chemical fertilizer</li>\r\n<li>Bio-fertilizer</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h4>Organic Fertilizer</h4>\r\n<p>It is formed by decomposition of dead and wastage of plants and animals. It is of 2 types.</p>\r\n<h5>Animal fertilizer</h5>\r\n<p>It is formed by decomposition of animal residue. It is of 2 types</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Compost Manure:It is formed of cowdung, poultry wastage, and kitchen garbage. It is prepared in small scale.</li>\r\n<li>Farmyard Manure:It is formed of cattle residue and crops residue. It can be produced in large scale &amp; use in field.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h5>Plant fertilizer (green manure)</h5>\r\n<p>Green manure is formed by decomposition of dead and wastage of green plants. It is also called humus layer. It increases the fertility of soil. [Maximum 30% to 50%].</p>\r\n<p>Plants used to prepare green manure are</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Crotolarla Juncea (sun hemp)</li>\r\n<li>Sesbania aculeata (Daincha)</li>\r\n<li>Sesbania rostrata</li>\r\n<li>Lens esculenta (mosoor)</li>\r\n<li>Leguminous plant</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Preparation of green manure</h4>\r\n<p>Before cultivation of crops, farmers cultivate the any of Crotolarla Juncea (sun hemp), Sesbania aculeata (Daincha), Sesbania rostrata, Lens esculenta (mosoor), and Leguminous plants. After maturation of these plants they plough them back under the soil where decomposition takes place and form green manure such manure is distributed throughout the field uniformly.</p>\r\n<h4>Importance</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The preparation of green manure is the most simple, cheapest and easiest method and can be applied by any person.</li>\r\n<li>It supplies organic and inorganic nutrients, nitrogenous substances and other important minerals.</li>\r\n<li>It has no bad aspects against biotic and abiotic components of environment.</li>\r\n<li>It enhances the quality of soil and water holding capacity as well as good aeration.</li>\r\n<li>It increases the maximum soil fertility (30-50%).</li>\r\n<li>It avoids soil erosion and landslides.</li>\r\n</ul>','2014-06-10 06:46:04',9,1,NULL,4,1,1,0),(55,'Crossing Over','<h4>Crossing over</h4>\r\n<p>It is a physical process in which genetic material is exchanged between <strong>non-sister chromatids of homologous</strong> chromosome during prophase-I of meosis through chaismata. It results in new genetic recombination.</p>\r\n<h5>Process of crossing over</h5>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Synapsis</strong></li>\r\n<ul>During Zygotene stage, paternal and maternal chromosome comes closer and pairs with each other which the phenomenon is called synapsis. Each pair of chromosomes is called Bivalent pair or homologous chromosome.</ul>\r\n<li><strong>Duplication</strong></li>\r\n<ul>All the requirements for meiosis are synthesized in Interphase. So replication of DNA and formation of chromatids are already incurred in interphase but do not distinct in other phase. During Duplication such 2 sister chromatids of each bivalent pairs are separated and distinct in Pachytene stage. So each bivalent pair has four (4) chromatids.</ul>\r\n<li><strong>Crossing Over</strong></li>\r\n<ul>In the Pachytene stage, the non-sister chromatids come closer in such a way that in certain points they attach and twisted point is called Chaismata. In Chaismata, breaking and rejoining of non-sister chromatids in crisscross way which is called crossing over.</ul>\r\n<li><strong>Terminalization</strong></li>\r\n<ul>After crossing over, each chaismata slides towards the end of the chromosome during Diplotene stage, then Chaismata are terminated then two chromosomes of each bivalent pair separates completely which is terminalization.</ul>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>In this way, crossing over takes place.</p>','2014-06-10 07:00:35',9,1,NULL,4,1,1,0),(56,'Introduction to Genetics','<h4>Genetics</h4>\n<p>Term &ldquo;Genetics&rdquo; was introduced by William Beteson in 1905. Genetics is the modern science in which we study about Heredity and Variation. And it is the vast subject which includes; Structure, number, behavior (normal &amp; abnormal) &amp; function of chromosome as well as Cell division; Mitosis-differentiation-growth &amp; development; Meosis-gamete-reproduction-young ones.</p>\n<h4>Heredity</h4>\n<p>In sexually reproducing organism certain characters are transferred from parent to progeny such character are called Heredity characters.</p>\n<p>Heredity can be defined as- &ldquo;It is a transmission of heredity characters from one generation to another through gametes.</p>\n<h5>Ancient views about heredity</h5>\n<p>Till 19<sup>th</sup> century people believed the theory of blending inheritance.</p>\n<p>According to this theory, male and female&rsquo;s substance mix together in the progeny &amp; blended then the progeny show intermediate characters between the parents, such concept was explained by different scientists in different way.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Moist vapor theory:- According to this theory, male introduce some male vapors inside the female body where these vapor are fused together to form embryo and that embryo develops into young ones.</li>\n<li>Fluid theory:- This theory was explained by Aristotle. According to it, female menstrual fluid mixed with the semen of male; after fertilization that mixture develops embryo and embryo into young ones.</li>\n<li>Preformation theory:- it is given by Leewenhook. As per it, there are some small tiny animalcules in the sperm and egg which is called Homuncules which are mixed and produced zygote that develops into organized body.</li>\n<li>Pangensis Theory:- Given by Darwin, proposes that there are some substances in the somatic cells which are transferred in the germ cells where they are fused and formed embryo develops into organized body.</li>\n<li>Epigenesis theory:- Given by Wolf, depicts that there are some unorganized substances in the germ cells which are fused and formed embryo develops into organized body.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>All the above theories failed to explain in some cases. E.g.:- Black horse crossed with White horse results Black Horse. Certain characters shown by progeny are not found in parents but found in grandparents. Thus, all these theories were discarded.</p>\n<p><strong>Later Gregor Johann Mendel also worked in the heredity and he explained that certain factors are transferred from parent to progeny which show similar and dissimilar characters. Nowadays the Mendel&rsquo;s factor is known as DNA or gene. Thus DNA is chemical basis of Heredity.</strong></p>\n<h4>Variation</h4>\n<p>Variation can be defined as a, morphological, physiological, and genetical differences among the progeny of same parent and with their parent. It is mainly caused by environmental factors or Genetical factors.</p>\n<h5>Types of variation</h5>\n<p>According to Types of cell:</p>\n<table class=\"tbl_list\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Somatic Variation</td>\n<td>Germinal variation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>The variation which takes place in the somatic cells is called somatic variation.</td>\n<td>The variation which takes place in germ cells, reproductive cells, is called germinal variation.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It is caused by environmental factors like adaptation, use and disuse of organs.</td>\n<td>It is caused by genetic factors like crossing over, hybridization, mutation.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Variation developed in a progeny is ended with its death; so it is external, temporary and non-heritable.</td>\n<td>It is permanent, internal and heritable.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>E.g. Seedling in presence of light = Green plantlet Seedling in absence of light = Yellow plantlet</td>\n<td>E.g. mule, Crossing over: different characters among sisters of same parent Mutation: 6 fingers in hand Hybridization: Pomato ( potato + tomato)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>According to degree of differences produced:</p>\n<table class=\"tbl_list\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Continuous Variation</td>\n<td>Discontinuous Variation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>In this type organism show very small indistinct changes which are caused by environmental factors.</td>\n<td>In this type, organism show drastic change which occurs suddenly &amp; caused by mutation.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It is temporary, common and non-heritable.</td>\n<td>It is permanent, extraordinary and heritable.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It is fluctuating, unstable and do not have role in evolution.</td>\n<td>It is stable and have significant role in evolution.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h5>Variation in asexually reproducing organisms</h5>\n<p>In some lower plants asexual reproduction takes place in which there is no gamete formation and no fertilization but only meosis occurs and produce no. of young plants. These young plants are similar among themselves and with their parents &amp; such plants are called clones. When such clones are grown in different environment (light, temperature, nutrition, water), they show variation in growth and development. Thus variation occurs in both sexually and asexually reproducing organisms.</p>\n<h5>Importance of variation</h5>\n<ol>\n<li>Variation provides unique character of living organism</li>\n<li>It helps plant and animals to adapt in changing environment.</li>\n<li>It produce new and better of living organism.</li>\n<li>It acts as raw material for evolution.</li>\n</ol>\n<h5>Difference between variation and heredity</h5>\n<table class=\"tbl_list\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Heredity</td>\n<td>Variation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It is transfer of heredity characters from parent to progeny.</td>\n<td>It is the morphological, physiological &amp; genetic materials among progeny of same parent with their parents.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It occurs in sexually reproducing organisms.</td>\n<td>It occurs in both organisms.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It is continuous.</td>\n<td>It is discontinuous.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It is caused by genetical factors.</td>\n<td>It is caused by both genetical and environmental factors.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It transports heredity character from one generation to other.</td>\n<td>It produces new and better type of living things.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>It plays indirectly in evolutional phase.</td>\n<td>It plays directly in evolution.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h4>Terminologies in Genetics</h4>\n<table class=\"tbl_list\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width=\"20%\">Terminology</td>\n<td>Meanings</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Gene</td>\n<td>A small segment of DNA which determines only one character of an organism</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Locus</td>\n<td>A specific position occupied by a gene on a specific chromosome; which is always constant for a gene</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Allele</td>\n<td>2 or more alternative forms of gene</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dominant Allele</td>\n<td>An allele of a gene which dominates other allele of the same gene. It is represented by capital letter.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Recessive allele</td>\n<td>An allele of a gene which is dominated by another allele of the same gene. It is represented in small letter. E.g. A gene of height in pea ha 2 alleles;\n<ul>\n<li>Dominant allele &shy;&shy;------- T</li>\n<li>Recessive allele---------t</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Genotype</td>\n<td>Genetic makeup of an organism</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Phenotype</td>\n<td>An external appearance &amp; physiological characters of an organism; determined by genotype and environment</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Homozygous</td>\n<td>Pure; an organism having two similar alleles of a gene; E.g. TT, tt</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Heterozygous</td>\n<td>Impure, an organism having 2 different alleles of a gene; E.g. Tt, tT</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mutation</td>\n<td>Sudden heritable changes in the genetic material of an organism</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Mutant</td>\n<td>An organism which has gone under mutation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Genetic cross</td>\n<td>A deliberate breeding between 2 organisms to produce a new organism having the character of both parent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Hybridization</td>\n<td>A genetic cross between 2 genetically different organisms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Parents</td>\n<td>The organism between whom a genetic cross is carried out</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Offspring</p>\n</td>\n<td>(Progeny); The organism obtained from a genetic cross</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Parent(P<sub>1</sub>) generation</td>\n<td>The generation of parent in a genetic cross</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Filial generation</td>\n<td>The generation of offspring in a genetic cross</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1<sup>st</sup> filial generation (F<sub>1)</sub></td>\n<td>The generation of offspring obtained by cross fertilization between parents</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2<sup>nd</sup> filial generation(F<sub>2</sub>)</td>\n<td>The generation of offspring obtained by self-fertilization in F<sub>1 </sub>generation</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Backcross</td>\n<td>A cross between F<sub>1 </sub>hybrid and any of the parents</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Test cross</td>\n<td>A cross between F<sub>1 </sub>&nbsp;hybrid and recessive parent</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Reciprocal cross</td>\n<td>Two crosses between 2 organisms, A &amp; B in the 1<sup>st</sup> of which, A acts as male parent and B acts as female parent ; while in the 2<sup>nd</sup> of which,&nbsp; A acts as female parent and B acts as male parent</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','2014-06-10 07:10:33',9,1,NULL,4,1,0,0),(57,'Grade 11 Physics Syllabus','<table class=\"tbl_list\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Unit-1</td>\n<td>Mechanics</td>\n<td>70 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1.</td>\n<td>Measurement of physical quantity - Need for measurements; System of Units; S.I. unit; Precision and significant figures; Dimensions; Main uses of dimensional equations.</td>\n<td>3 hrs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2.</td>\n<td>Scalars and Vectors - Graphical presentation of vectors; Addition and subtraction of vectors: Parallelogram, Triangle and Polygon law of vectors; Resolution of vectors; Unit vectors; Scalar and Vector Products.</td>\n<td>6 hrs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3.</td>\n<td>Kinematics - Uniform and non-uniform motion; Average velocity and acceleration; Instantaneous velocity and acceleration; Equation of motion (graphical treatment); Motion of a freely falling body; Relative velocity; Projectile motion.</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4.</td>\n<td>Laws of Motion &ndash; Newton&rsquo;s Law of motion; Inertia, force, Linear momentum, Impulse, Conservation of Linear momentum; Free-body diagrams; Solid frictions; Laws of solid friction and their verifications; Applications of Newton&rsquo;s laws: Particles in Equilibrium, Dynamics of Particles</td>\n<td>8 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5.</td>\n<td>Work and Energy &ndash; Work; Work done by a constant force and a variable force; Power; Energy: Kinetic Energy; Work-energy theorem, Potential energy; Conservation of Energy; Conservative and non-conservative forces; Elastic and inelastic Collision</td>\n<td>4 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6.</td>\n<td>Circular Motion &ndash; Angular displacement, velocity and acceleration, Relation between angular and linear velocity and acceleration; Centripetal acceleration; Centripetal force; Conical Pendulum; Motion in a vertical circle; Motion of Cars and cyclist around a banked track</td>\n<td>5 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7.</td>\n<td>Gravitation &ndash; Newton&rsquo;s laws of gravitation; acceleration due to gravity; g; Mass and weight; Gravitational field strength, Variation in value of &lsquo;g&rsquo; due to altitude, Depth and rotation of earth; Weightlessness; Motion of a satellite: Orbital velocity, height and time period of a satellite, Geostationary Satellite, Potential and Kinetic energy of a satellite; Gravitational potential: Gravitational Potential energy; Escape Velocity; Black holes</td>\n<td>9 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>8.</td>\n<td>Equilibrium &ndash; Moment of Forces; Torque; Torque due to a couple; Center of mass; Center of Gravity; Conditions of equilibrium</td>\n<td>2 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9.</td>\n<td>Rotational Dynamics &ndash; Rotation of rigid bodies; Equation of angular motion; Relation between linear and angular kinematics; Kinetic energy of rotation of rigid bodies; Moment of inertia; Radius of Gyration; Moment of inertia of uniform rod; Torque and angular momentum for a rigid body; Work and Power in rotational motion; Angular momentum; Conservation of angular momentum</td>\n<td>8 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10.</td>\n<td>Elasticity &ndash; Hooke&rsquo;s law: Force constant, Verification of Hooke&rsquo;s law; Stress; Strain; Elasticity and Plasticity; Elastic modulus; Young modulus and its determination, Bulk modulus, Shear Modulus, Poisson&rsquo;s ratio, Elastic Potential energy</td>\n<td>6 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11.</td>\n<td>Periodic Motion &ndash; Oscillatory motion; Circle of reference; Equation of Simple Harmonic Motion (SHM); Energy in SHM; Application of SHM; Simple Pendulum; Damped Oscillation; Forced Oscillation and resonance</td>\n<td>6 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12.</td>\n<td>Fluid Mechanics &ndash; Fluid statics: Density; Pressure in a fluid; Archimedes Principle; Buoyancy surface tension; Molecular theory of surface tension; Surface energy; Angle of Contact and capillarity; Measurement of coefficient of surface tension by capillary tube method. Fluid dynamics: Newton&rsquo;s formula for viscosity in a liquid; Coefficient of viscosity; Laminar and turbulent flow; Poiseuille&rsquo;s formula; Stokes law and its applications; Measurement of viscosity of viscous liquid; Equation of Continuity; Bernoulli&rsquo;s equation and its applications</td>\n<td>10 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Unit 2</td>\n<td>Heat and thermodynamics</td>\n<td>40 teaching hours</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1.</td>\n<td>Heat and temperature- Concept of temperature; Thermal equilibrium, Thermal expansion and their relation; Measurement of linear expansivity, liquid Expansion: Absolute and apparent expansion of liquid, Measurement of absolute expansivity by Dulong and Petit method</td>\n<td>5 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2.</td>\n<td>Quantity of heat- Heat capacity and specific heat capacity; Newton&rsquo;s law of cooling; Measurement of specific heat capacity of solids by the method of mixture and of liquids by the method cooling. Change of phase: Latent heat, specific latent heat of fusion, and vaporization and their measurements by the method of mixture</td>\n<td>5 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3.</td>\n<td>Thermal Properties of Matter &ndash;Equation of state: Ideal gas equation; P &ndash; V diagram; Molecular properties of matter; Kinetic - molecular model of ideal gas: Derivation of pressure exerted by gas, Average translational kinetic energy of gas molecule; Boltzmann constant, Root mean square speed; Heat capacities; Heat capacities of gases and solids</td>\n<td>8 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4.</td>\n<td>Hygrometry &ndash; Saturated and unsaturated vapor pressure; Boiling point; Triple point and critical point; Dew point, Absolute humidity; Relative humidity and its determination</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5.</td>\n<td>Transfer of heat- conduction Thermal conductivity and its determination by Searle&rsquo;s method; Convection; Conduction: convective coefficient Radiation: Ideal radiator; Black body radiation Stefan- Boltzmann law</td>\n<td>4 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6.</td>\n<td>First law of thermodynamics &ndash; Direction of thermodynamic processes; Work done during volume change, Heat and Work; Internal energy and First law of thermodynamics; Thermodynamic processes: Adiabatic, Isochoric, Isothermal Isobaric processes; Heat capacities of ideal gas at constant pressure and volume and relation between them; Isothermal and Adiabatic processes for ideal gas.</td>\n<td>9 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7.</td>\n<td>Second law of thermodynamics- Direction of Thermodynamic processes; Second law of thermodynamics; Heat engines; Internal combustion engines: Otto Cycle, Diesel Cycle; Carnot cycle; Kelvin temperature scale; Refrigerators; Entropy and disorder(Introduction only)</td>\n<td>6 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Unit 3</td>\n<td>Geometric optics</td>\n<td>20 teaching hours</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1.</td>\n<td>Photometry, Reflection of curved mirrors- Convex and concave mirrors; Image in Spherical mirrors, Mirrors formula; Real and virtual images.</td>\n<td>2 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2.</td>\n<td>Refraction of plane surfaces- Laws of refraction: Refractive index; Relation between refractive index; Lateral shift; Total internal reflection and its application; critical angle; optical fiber.</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3.</td>\n<td>Refraction through prisms- Minimum deviation and refractive index; Deviation in small angle prism.</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4.</td>\n<td>Lenses &ndash; Spherical lenses; thin lens formula; Power of lens; Combination of thin lenses in contact.</td>\n<td>4 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5.</td>\n<td>Dispersion &ndash; Spectrum; Spectrometer; Pure spectrum; Dispersive power; Achromatic lenses; Condition for achromatic lenses in contact, Chromatic aberration Spherical aberration; Scattering of light- blue color of the sky.</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>6.</td>\n<td>Optical instrument - The human eye; Defects of vision and their correction; Visual angle; Angular magnification; Magnifier; Camera; Compound microscope, Astronomical telescope( Reflection And Refractive type)</td>\n<td>5 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Unit 4</td>\n<td>Electrostatics</td>\n<td>20 teaching hours</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1.</td>\n<td>Electrostatics- Electric charge: Electric charges; Conductor and insulators; Charging by induction, Coulomb&rsquo;s law- Force between two point charges, Force between multiple electric charges</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2.</td>\n<td>Electric field &ndash; Electric fields; Calculation of electric field due to point charges; Field lines. Gauss law: Electric Flux; Gauss law and its application: Field of a charged sphere, line charge plane sheet of charge.</td>\n<td>7 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3.</td>\n<td>Potential: Potential and potential difference, Potential due to a point charge; Equipotential lines and surfaces; Potential gradient; Potential energy, Electron volt.</td>\n<td>3 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>4.</td>\n<td>Capacitance and dielectrics &ndash; capacitance and capacitors; Charging and discharging of capacitors through a resistor; Parallel plate capacitors; Combination of capacitors; Energy of charged capacitor; Effect of a dielectric; Molecular theory of induced charges; Polarization and displacement.</td>\n<td>7 hrs</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','2014-06-08 01:17:50',1,3,0,1,1,0,0),(58,'Biology Syllabus','<table class=\"tbl_list\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"32\">\r\n<p><strong>Unit</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Content</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"85\">\r\n<p><strong>Teaching Hours</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"2\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>1</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Introduction&nbsp; to Biology</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"2\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>10</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Biomolecule</strong>: (General Concepts)carbohydrate, protein, lipid, nucleic acid, minerals and water</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"3\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>2</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Cell Biology</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"3\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>15</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>The cell, cell as a unit of life, structure of prokaryotes and&nbsp; eukaryotes; structure and function of cell organelles and cell inclusions</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Cell divisions</strong>: Amitosis, mitosis, meiosis</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"8\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>3</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Biodiversity</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"8\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Definition and scope of biodiversity</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Phylogeny; Two kingdoms classification, drawbacks; The five kingdoms classification:&nbsp; Monera, Protista, Mycota, Plantae, and Animalia</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Monera</strong>: Bacteria- structure, function, lifestyle and economic importance; Cynobacteria: Nostoc- structure, reproduction, and economic importance</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Mycota</strong>: Concept of Zygomycetes, Ascomycetes, Basidomycetes &amp; Deuteromycetes; Structure and reproduction of Zygomycetes(Mucor), Ascomycetes (Yeast); Economic importance of Fungi</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Plantae</strong> : <em>Algae:</em> Concept of red and green algae, structure and reproduction of spirogyra; <em>Bryophytes</em>: Marchantia &amp; Funaria (morphology&nbsp; and life cycle); <em>Pteridophyta</em>: Dryopteris (morphology&nbsp; and life cycle); <em>Gymnosperm</em>: brief morphological structure on Cycas &amp; Pinus; <em>Angiosperm</em>: Morphology (root, stem, leaf, flower, seed), Taxonomy &amp; Economic importance of Cruciferae (Brassicaceae), Solanaceae, Leguminosae &ndash; Papilonaceae, Compositae (Asteraceae), Graminaceae (Poaceae);</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Lichen:</strong> Introduction and Economic importance</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Virus:</strong> Structure and Economic importance</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"7\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>4</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Biota and Their Environment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"7\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>15 hrs</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Ecology</strong>: Defination, biotic &amp;abiotic factors and their interaction; Concept of Ecosystem, pond and grass land ecosystem, structural and functional aspects; Food chain, ecological pyramids, Productivity, concept of community and succession</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Bio-geo-chemical cycle:</strong> Carbon &amp; Nitrogen Cycle</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Ecological imbalance and consequences: </strong>Greenhouse effect, Depletion of ozone</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Concept of mountain ecosystem: </strong>altitude &amp; climatic changes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Adaptation:</strong>&nbsp; Hydrophyte, Mesophyte &amp; xerophyte</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Conservation: </strong>Forest conservation, introduction to forest of Nepal, importance of forest and hazards of deforestation</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Biology: Zoology</strong></p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"32\">\r\n<p>Unit</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Content</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"85\">\r\n<p>Teaching Hours</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"3\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>1</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Introduction&nbsp; to Biology</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"3\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>10</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Nature and scope, Branches</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>General approach to understand life process</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"4\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>2</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Evolution of Life</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"4\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>15</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Meaning of evolution, History of evolutionary ideas</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Life and its origin, oparin and Haldance\'s Theory, Miller &ndash; Urey experiment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Organic evolution, evidences: structural, anatomical, paleontology, embryological, biochemical &amp; genetical; <strong>Lamarckism, Darwinism</strong> &amp; concept of <strong>Neo-Darwinism; Human Evolution</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"4\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>3</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Biodiversity</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"4\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Definition and scope of biodiversity, Faunal diversity in Nepal</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Protista</strong>: General characteristics &amp; classification of phylum Protozoa With Examples; Habit &amp; Habitat, structure, reproduction, &amp; lifecycle of Paramecium &amp; Plasmodium vivax</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Animalia: </strong>General characteristics &amp; classification of phyla with examples- Porifera, Coelenterata(cnidarian), Platyhelminthes, Aschelminthes, Annelida, Arthropoda, Mollusca, Echinodermata &amp; Chordata</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>&nbsp; <strong>Earthworm (Pheretima posthuma): </strong>habit and habitat, structure, digestive, circulatory, excretory, reproductive and nervous systems; Economic importance</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Frog (Rana tigrina): </strong>habit and habitat, structure, digestive, circulatory, excretory, Respiratory, reproductive, urinogenital and nervous systems;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"5\" width=\"32\">\r\n<p>4</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p>Biota &amp; their Environment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td rowspan=\"5\" width=\"85\">\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Environmental pollution : </strong>Air, water, soil, pollution; source, effect and control measures and hazards of pesticides</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Animal behavior : </strong>Taxis, reflexes &amp; reflex action, dominance &amp; leadership, Migratory behavior of Fish &amp; Birds</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Adaptation: </strong>Animal- aquatic, amphibious &amp; terrestrial (Arboreal and Volant)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"617\">\r\n<p><strong>Conservation:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>&nbsp; Wildlife conservation: Meaning of wildlife, importance; meaning of rare, threatened, vulnerable, and endangered species; few endangered species in Nepal.</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp; Management of land &amp; water: Human responsibility for the protection of earth.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','2014-06-08 04:37:39',3,3,0,4,3,0,0),(59,'Grade 12 English Syllabus','<h5>Compulsory English</h5>\n<p><strong>Grade &ndash; XI &nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Full Marks 100</strong></p>\n<p><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&